// Content Sprint 1: Onboarding journey and marketplace decisions.
window.CONTENT_SPRINT_1 = {"onboarding-overview":{"summary":"Understand what happens during onboarding, how responsibilities are shared, which stages and milestones move the implementation forward, and how to prepare the internal team that will own the marketplace after launch.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Project team","Executive sponsor","Workstream owners"],"sections":{"What Happens During Onboarding":"<p>Onboarding turns your marketplace strategy into an operating marketplace. You will make business decisions, configure your marketplace in Marketplacer, prepare connected systems, onboard Sellers and products, test end-to-end customer journeys and confirm that your teams can support live operations.</p><div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Align the programme</strong><p>Confirm the scope, stakeholders, environments, target date and known dependencies.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Design the experience</strong><p>Map customer, Seller and internal journeys and identify decisions that need ownership.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Build team capability</strong><p>Complete role-based training and apply each decision to configuration and procedures.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Onboard Sellers and products</strong><p>Create Seller accounts, connect systems, import products and validate catalogue quality.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Validate launch readiness</strong><p>Complete end-to-end testing, close launch-critical gaps and approve go-live.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">6</span><div><strong>Transition to business as usual</strong><p>Move from implementation into steady-state operations, with clear ownership for day-to-day marketplace management, support and continuous improvement.</p></div></div></div><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Start with decisions, not settings.</strong> A platform setting should implement an approved commercial, customer or operational position.</div>","Operator and Marketplacer Responsibilities":"<p>Marketplacer Delivery guides the onboarding programme, explains platform capabilities and helps your team understand the decisions and configuration required. Your organisation remains accountable for the business model, customer policies, seller terms, connected systems and operational readiness.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Your organisation</th><th>Marketplacer</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Appoint the marketplace lead and workstream owners</td><td>Guide the implementation sequence and onboarding activities</td></tr><tr><td>Approve commercial, customer and operating decisions</td><td>Explain relevant capabilities, dependencies and common approaches</td></tr><tr><td>Configure or approve your front end, payments and integrations</td><td>Prepare and support the Marketplacer environments</td></tr><tr><td>Recruit, contract and prepare sellers</td><td>Train your team to configure and operate the platform</td></tr><tr><td>Own customer service, finance and daily marketplace operations</td><td>Support validation, launch readiness and handover</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Shared implementation does not mean shared accountability.</strong> Record a named owner for every decision and every implementation task.</div>","Typical Implementation Stages":"<div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Initiation</h3><p>Establish governance, environments, access, timing and risks.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Discovery</h3><p>Map customer and seller journeys and confirm the operating model.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Training and configuration</h3><p>Build internal capability while applying approved decisions in Sandbox and Production.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Seller and catalogue onboarding</h3><p>Prepare live sellers, products, mappings, shipping and operational processes.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Testing and launch</h3><p>Validate complete journeys, approve readiness and support the first live transactions.</p></article></div><p>Stages overlap. For example, seller discussions may begin while training is underway, and integration testing may continue while catalogue work progresses. Manage dependencies rather than treating every stage as a strict handoff.</p>","Key Milestones":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Milestone</th><th>Evidence of completion</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Kickoff complete</td><td>Governance, environments, training plan and target launch approach agreed</td></tr><tr><td>Customer journey mapped</td><td>Customer touchpoints, owners, systems and exceptions documented</td></tr><tr><td>Seller strategy agreed</td><td>Launch sellers, proposition, connection methods and onboarding approach defined</td></tr><tr><td>Training complete</td><td>Relevant teams can perform their required platform and operational tasks</td></tr><tr><td>Configuration ready</td><td>Launch-critical settings approved, applied and tested</td></tr><tr><td>Live sellers ready</td><td>Accounts, agreements, products, shipping, fulfilment and training completed</td></tr><tr><td>End-to-end validation passed</td><td>Successful product, order, fulfilment, cancellation, return, refund and finance scenarios</td></tr><tr><td>Go-live approved</td><td>Risks accepted, support coverage confirmed and launch owners assigned</td></tr><tr><td>Customer Success handover complete</td><td>Ongoing owners, cadence, open actions and support routes documented</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","Who Should Be Involved":"<p>Bring the people who own the decision or the future process. Attendance should change by topic rather than relying on one project representative to answer every question.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Workstream</th><th>Typical contribution</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Marketplace leadership</td><td>Strategy, scope, priorities, escalation and go-live approval</td></tr><tr><td>Commercial and seller teams</td><td>Seller proposition, contracts, commission or wholesale terms and recruitment</td></tr><tr><td>Customer experience and service</td><td>Customer journeys, communications, cancellations, returns and complaints</td></tr><tr><td>Catalogue and ecommerce</td><td>Taxonomy, product standards, mapping, search, merchandising and publication</td></tr><tr><td>Finance and tax</td><td>Tax, fees, refunds, remittances, payouts and reconciliation</td></tr><tr><td>Technology and integrations</td><td>Front end, APIs, MConnect, webhooks, monitoring and recovery</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplace operations</td><td>Configuration, seller onboarding, daily queues and cross-team coordination</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","Preparing Your Internal Team":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Nominate one marketplace lead with authority to coordinate decisions and escalate blockers.</li><li>Assign accountable owners for customer experience, seller strategy, catalogue, finance, operations and technology.</li><li>Protect time for training, configuration, seller onboarding and testing.</li><li>Create a shared decision register, action tracker and risk log.</li><li>Give team members access to the correct environments and supporting systems.</li><li>Agree how decisions are approved and how Production changes are controlled.</li><li>Plan who will own each process after the implementation project ends.</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Prepare the operating team before launch.</strong> The marketplace should not depend on the implementation team remaining available indefinitely.</div>"},"related":[["kickoff-project-initiation","Kickoff and Project Initiation"],["how-decisions-work","How Marketplace Decisions Work"],["onboarding-to-launch","From Onboarding to Launch"]]},"kickoff-project-initiation":{"summary":"Confirm the onboarding plan, prepare the Marketplacer environments, organise access and training, align the onboarding checklist and target launch date, and identify any risks or dependencies that could affect launch.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Project manager","Environment Manager","Workstream leads"],"sections":{"What the Kickoff Covers":"<p>Kickoff creates a shared starting point for your organisation and Marketplacer Delivery. Use it to confirm what is being launched, who owns each workstream and how progress and decisions will be managed.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Marketplace vision, launch scope and success measures</li><li>Project governance, contacts and escalation</li><li>Production and Sandbox environments</li><li>Internal and Marketplacer responsibilities</li><li>Training sequence and expected attendees</li><li>Customer Journey Mapping and Seller Strategy sessions</li><li>Seller, product, front-end, payment and integration dependencies</li><li>Target launch date and major milestones</li><li>Risks, assumptions and immediate actions</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Kickoff is an alignment session, not a requirement to have every decision finalised.</strong> Record unresolved questions with an owner and required-by date.</div>","Environment Manager":"<p>Nominate the person who will receive and manage initial environment access. The Environment Manager should understand your internal access process and be able to coordinate administrator access for the wider team.</p><div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Select the right person</h3><p>Choose someone available throughout onboarding who can work across technology and business teams.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Protect access</h3><p>Use individual accounts, appropriate permissions and your internal security standards.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Plan continuity</h3><p>Nominate a backup and document how environment administration will be handed over after launch.</p></article></div><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Use individual administrator accounts.</strong> Individual access supports security, accountability and easier offboarding.</div>","Production and Sandbox Creation":"<p>Marketplacer prepares a Production environment for live marketplace operations and a Sandbox environment for configuration, training and testing. Treat Production as the live source of truth and use Sandbox to validate changes before applying them where practical.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Environment</th><th>Use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Sandbox</td><td>Training, trial configuration, sample sellers and products, integration testing and end-to-end rehearsal</td></tr><tr><td>Production</td><td>Approved live configuration, live sellers and products, customer orders, financial records and operational reporting</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Confirm marketplace name and environment contacts.</li><li>Confirm tax model and other creation-time requirements before the environments are provisioned.</li><li>Record environment URLs and administrator access.</li><li>Agree how Sandbox will be refreshed and what must be rechecked afterwards.</li><li>Keep test data and credentials separate from Production.</li></ul>","Team Access Requirements":"<p>Prepare access according to the tasks each person will perform. Avoid giving broad administrator permissions simply because onboarding is moving quickly.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>Typical access need</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Marketplace lead</td><td>Broad visibility and configuration oversight</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplace operations</td><td>Seller, product, order, refund and reporting access</td></tr><tr><td>Catalogue team</td><td>Categories, brands, mapping, product governance and reporting</td></tr><tr><td>Finance</td><td>Commercial configuration, sales, refunds, remittances and finance reports</td></tr><tr><td>Customer service</td><td>Orders, shipments, cancellations, returns and refund visibility</td></tr><tr><td>Technology</td><td>Integration credentials, webhooks, identifiers and troubleshooting views</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Collect names and work email addresses.</li><li>Confirm the person approving access.</li><li>Apply least-privilege permissions.</li><li>Enable MFA where required.</li><li>Test access before each training session.</li><li>Plan the removal of temporary implementation access.</li></ul>","Training Schedule":"<p>Schedule training early enough for your teams to apply each topic during implementation. Invite the people who will make the related decisions and operate the process after launch.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Training area</th><th>Recommended attendees</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Platform Foundations and Setup</td><td>Marketplace lead, operations and technology</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplace Structure and Commercials</td><td>Catalogue, ecommerce, commercial, finance and tax</td></tr><tr><td>Seller, Product and Order Operations</td><td>Seller team, catalogue, operations, fulfilment and technology</td></tr><tr><td>Refunds and Marketplace Finance</td><td>Customer service, finance, operations and integrations</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Treat training as working sessions.</strong> Bring your marketplace decisions, seller examples and test scenarios so the team can apply the capability rather than only observe it.</div>","Onboarding Checklist":"<p>Use one shared onboarding checklist to connect decisions, tasks, owners, due dates and evidence. Keep the checklist current rather than creating separate private trackers for each team.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Assign an owner to every task.</li><li>Set due dates against the earliest dependency.</li><li>Record blockers, decisions and supporting links.</li><li>Separate Sandbox, Production and external-system actions.</li><li>Track seller and integration readiness individually.</li><li>Retain evidence for testing and go-live approval.</li><li>Review the checklist at the regular project meeting.</li></ul>","Target Launch Date":"<p>Use the target date to organise dependencies, not as a promise made before scope and readiness are understood. Validate the date against front-end development, payments, integrations, seller contracting, product onboarding, testing and operational capacity.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Date confidence</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Working target</td><td>Useful for planning while material dependencies remain open</td></tr><tr><td>Forecast date</td><td>Supported by current plans, owners and delivery evidence</td></tr><tr><td>Committed date</td><td>Approved with launch scope, testing and support plans controlled</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Protect essential testing when reviewing the target date.</strong> Adjust scope or timing when launch-critical customer, financial or integration risks remain unresolved.</div>","Initial Risks and Dependencies":"<p>Record risks and dependencies during kickoff and review them throughout onboarding.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Business</td><td>Unapproved operating model, unclear customer ownership or changing launch scope</td></tr><tr><td>Seller</td><td>No signed seller, delayed technical contact, weak product data or incomplete agreement</td></tr><tr><td>Catalogue</td><td>Taxonomy not final, missing attributes, large unmapped range or unclear source of truth</td></tr><tr><td>Technology</td><td>Front-end delay, payment dependency, unowned API, webhook or monitoring gap</td></tr><tr><td>Finance</td><td>Tax uncertainty, commission not approved, remittance or refund treatment unclear</td></tr><tr><td>Operations</td><td>Insufficient customer service, catalogue or finance capacity</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Record the owner.</li><li>Describe the impact.</li><li>Set a mitigation or decision.</li><li>Identify the date at which it becomes launch-critical.</li><li>Escalate when the mitigation is not progressing.</li></ul>"},"related":[["onboarding-overview","Onboarding Overview"],["customer-journey-mapping","Customer Journey Mapping"],["decision-timeline","Decision Timeline"]]},"customer-journey-mapping":{"summary":"Prepare for a facilitated review of the customer experience before and after purchase, identify friction points, and translate customer expectations into marketplace, front-end and operational requirements.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Product","Customer service","Technology"],"sections":{"About the Session":"<p>Customer Journey Mapping connects the experience shoppers will see with the processes and systems that must operate behind it. Walk through the proposed journey from discovery through checkout, fulfilment, returns and support.</p><div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Who should attend</h3><p>Marketplace leadership, front-end product owners, customer service, operations, payments and integration owners.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>What to prepare</h3><p>A live or staging journey, mock-up, Miro board, slides or a verbal walkthrough, plus known policies and technical constraints.</p></article></div><h3>Expected outcome</h3><p>Create a shared view of what the customer experiences, where Marketplacer participates, which system owns each step and which decisions or investigations remain open.</p><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Bring the journey you already have.</strong> The aim is to expose assumptions and dependencies, not to assess the format of your documentation.</div>","Before Purchase":"<p>Walk through how customers reach the marketplace, discover products and understand who is selling them.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Entry points, authentication and account creation</li><li>Navigation, collections, search and filters</li><li>Product pages, seller identity and product ownership</li><li>Pricing, promotions, loyalty benefits and availability</li><li>Delivery promises before the product reaches the cart</li><li>Product questions and customer support before purchase</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Decide how visible sellers will be.</strong> Confirm where seller name, delivery promise, returns information and seller-specific details appear.</div>","Checkout and Payment":"<p>Review the transition from product selection to a confirmed marketplace order. Your front-end checkout may sit outside Marketplacer, but it determines the order and financial information Marketplacer receives.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Questions to resolve</th><th>Typical owner</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Multi-seller cart</td><td>How are separate sellers, shipments and delivery charges presented?</td><td>Front-end product</td></tr><tr><td>Payment</td><td>When is payment authorised or captured, and which provider executes it?</td><td>Payments and Finance</td></tr><tr><td>Order submission</td><td>Is the order sent immediately or after a hold?</td><td>Technology and Operations</td></tr><tr><td>Tax and fees</td><td>How are tax, postage, promotions and marketplace charges represented?</td><td>Finance</td></tr><tr><td>Failure recovery</td><td>What happens when payment succeeds but order creation fails?</td><td>Technology and Customer service</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Confirm the system boundary.</strong> Marketplacer records marketplace orders and seller invoices. Your storefront and payment provider still have responsibilities that must be documented.</div>","After Purchase":"<p>Map what happens after checkout, particularly when one customer order contains products from more than one seller.</p><div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Customer order confirmed</strong><p>The storefront confirms the purchase and communicates the initial delivery expectation.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Seller invoices created</strong><p>Marketplace items are split into seller-level records for fulfilment and finance.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Sellers dispatch</strong><p>Each seller may use a different carrier, tracking number and dispatch date.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Customer receives updates</strong><p>Order history and communications represent split shipments and remaining items clearly.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Exceptions are managed</strong><p>Customer service can identify the correct seller, shipment and operational owner.</p></div></div></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Order history and marketplace item identification</li><li>Seller notification and acknowledgement</li><li>Partial fulfilment and split shipments</li><li>Tracking and delivery updates</li><li>Failed delivery and lost parcel processes</li><li>Seller non-response and escalation</li></ul>","Cancellations, Returns and Refunds":"<p>Align customer expectations with seller permissions, marketplace policy, front-end capabilities and payment processing.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Customer cancellation eligibility before dispatch</li><li>Order hold or immediate seller release</li><li>Post-dispatch return request channel</li><li>Marketplace-wide or seller-specific return policy</li><li>Return Required and returnless criteria</li><li>Return label, address, collection and shipping funding</li><li>Seller assessment and operator override</li><li>Payment refund ownership and customer timeframe</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Separate the customer experience from the operational workflow.</strong> A return portal can make the request easy while Marketplacer records seller actions, financial adjustments and remittance effects behind the scenes.</div>","Customer Journey Outputs":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Output</th><th>What it should contain</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Journey map</td><td>Customer steps, system touchpoints, communications and exception paths</td></tr><tr><td>Decision list</td><td>Open and confirmed decisions, owners and required-by dates</td></tr><tr><td>Integration dependencies</td><td>Order, payment, fulfilment, cancellation and refund behaviours requiring technical work</td></tr><tr><td>Operational actions</td><td>Processes for customer service, sellers, finance and marketplace operations</td></tr><tr><td>Testing scenarios</td><td>End-to-end scenarios that must be proven before launch</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Update the Marketplace Decision Register after the session.</strong> Customer Journey Mapping often surfaces decisions that cannot be finalised in the meeting but must be owned and tracked.</div>"},"related":[["seller-strategy-session","Seller Strategy"],["customer-experience-decisions","Customer Experience Decisions"],["marketplace-decision-register","Marketplace Decision Register"]]},"seller-strategy-session":{"summary":"Prepare the seller proposition, launch and post-launch seller pipeline, connection methods, commercial readiness, onboarding approach and performance expectations needed to build sustainable marketplace supply.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Commercial and seller teams","Operations","Technology"],"sections":{"About the Session":"<p>The Seller Strategy session turns growth ambitions into a practical launch and onboarding plan. Review who you want to recruit, why they should join, how they will connect, what they must provide and who owns each stage from outreach to live trading.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Marketplace value proposition for sellers</li><li>Launch seller and product scope</li><li>Post-launch recruitment approach</li><li>Commercial readiness and seller agreement</li><li>Seller technology and connection methods</li><li>Product onboarding assistance and support boundaries</li><li>Training, testing and launch readiness</li><li>Performance expectations and enforcement</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Bring real seller examples.</strong> Connection method, catalogue size, product quality and operational maturity determine how much onboarding effort each seller requires.</div>","Marketplace Seller Proposition":"<p>Define the reasons a seller should invest time, technology and catalogue effort in your marketplace.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Proposition area</th><th>Questions</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Customer access</td><td>Which audience, demand or loyalty proposition can the seller reach?</td></tr><tr><td>Commercial value</td><td>What sales, brand, data or strategic opportunity exists?</td></tr><tr><td>Operational model</td><td>Who owns customer service, fulfilment, returns and payments?</td></tr><tr><td>Technology</td><td>How easily can the seller connect and maintain products and orders?</td></tr><tr><td>Support</td><td>What onboarding, training and ongoing account support will you provide?</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Keep the proposition accurate. Align Seller commitments with approved scope, confirmed capability and available resources.</p>","Launch and Post-Launch Sellers":"<p>Separate the launch group from the long-term recruitment pipeline.</p><div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Launch sellers</h3><p>Choose a manageable group that can supply a representative range, respond quickly and participate in testing.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Post-launch sellers</h3><p>Build the next pipeline around category gaps, customer demand and the operational capacity to onboard them well.</p></article></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Target number of launch sellers</li><li>Minimum category and product coverage</li><li>Named seller prospects and current stage</li><li>Fallback sellers if a launch seller slips</li><li>Post-launch recruitment priorities</li><li>Owner for outreach, pipeline progression and signed agreement</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Seller recruitment and seller onboarding are separate processes.</strong> Define the exact handoff from prospecting and agreement to technical and operational onboarding.</div>","Seller Technology and Connection Method":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Best suited to</th><th>Key preparation</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller Portal</td><td>Smaller ranges and sellers managing products and orders manually</td><td>Role training, product standards and operational capacity</td></tr><tr><td>Bulk Product Management</td><td>Structured catalogue files and periodic bulk maintenance</td><td>Identifiers, templates, mapping and error correction</td></tr><tr><td>MConnect</td><td>Supported ecommerce platforms requiring prebuilt product, order and fulfilment flows</td><td>Credentials, product selection, synced fields and testing</td></tr><tr><td>Custom API or partner</td><td>Complex systems, high scale or bespoke workflows</td><td>Architecture, ownership, monitoring, retries and support</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Select the method after understanding the seller system, product count, update frequency, order process, fulfilment process and technical resources.</p>","Commercial Readiness":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Commercial model approved</li><li>Commission, wholesale, postage and fee treatment agreed</li><li>Promotion and refund funding defined</li><li>Remittance and payout terms confirmed</li><li>Seller agreement ready</li><li>Tax and compliance requirements clear</li><li>Internal approval authority documented</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Confirm the core terms before full onboarding begins.</strong> Late commercial changes can require seller reconfiguration, retesting and agreement variations.</div>","Seller Onboarding Approach":"<p>Define a repeatable seller journey while allowing for genuine differences in technology, catalogue and risk.</p><div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Qualify</strong><p>Confirm proposition fit, commercial readiness and operational capability.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Contract</strong><p>Complete seller agreement and required business information.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Configure</strong><p>Create the seller account and apply commercial, shipping, refund and performance settings.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Connect and onboard products</strong><p>Choose the connection method, import a controlled range, map and remediate data.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Train and test</strong><p>Prove order, fulfilment, cancellation, return and finance workflows.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">6</span><div><strong>Launch and stabilise</strong><p>Approve the seller, monitor first orders and hand over to ongoing management.</p></div></div></div><p>State exactly what help you provide for initial product onboarding and what remains the seller’s responsibility afterwards.</p>","Seller Performance Expectations":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Expectation examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Catalogue</td><td>Accurate products, valid identifiers, approved categories and timely correction</td></tr><tr><td>Inventory</td><td>Reliable availability and low stock-related cancellation</td></tr><tr><td>Fulfilment</td><td>Dispatch within SLA and valid tracking</td></tr><tr><td>Returns</td><td>Timely assessment and policy-consistent outcomes</td></tr><tr><td>Service</td><td>Response within agreed timeframes and cooperation during incidents</td></tr><tr><td>Compliance</td><td>Current evidence and immediate action on safety or restricted-product concerns</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Include performance standards in seller communications and agreements, and define the consequences of repeated breach.</p>","Seller Strategy Outputs":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Output</th><th>Required content</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller proposition</td><td>Approved benefits, responsibilities and support model</td></tr><tr><td>Launch seller plan</td><td>Named sellers, range, stage, connection method and launch target</td></tr><tr><td>Recruitment ownership</td><td>Outreach, pipeline, agreement and onboarding handoff owners</td></tr><tr><td>Onboarding model</td><td>Stages, documents, training, product assistance and readiness criteria</td></tr><tr><td>Commercial readiness plan</td><td>Terms, agreement, configuration and approvals still required</td></tr><tr><td>Performance framework</td><td>SLAs, monitoring, review cadence and enforcement</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Update the seller tracker after the session.</strong> Record seller-specific dependencies rather than relying on one general marketplace plan.</div><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Put your Seller Strategy into action with the Recruit stage.</strong> The <a href=\"https://sites.google.com/marketplacer.com/mp-seller-playbook-v1/marketplacer-seller-playbook\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Marketplacer Seller Playbook</a> includes practical resources for Seller recruitment, pipeline management, Seller standards, pitch preparation, discovery surveys, scorecards and onboarding tracking.<div class=\"standalone-actions\"><a class=\"resource-action\" href=\"https://sites.google.com/marketplacer.com/mp-seller-playbook-v1/marketplacer-seller-playbook\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Explore the Recruit resources</a></div><p>Some linked templates or internal resources may require assistance from your Marketplacer representative.</p></div>"},"related":[["seller-strategy-decisions","Seller Strategy Decisions"],["seller-lifecycle","Seller Lifecycle"],["onboarding-to-launch","From Onboarding to Launch"]]},"training-programme":{"summary":"Use a role-based training programme to build the knowledge your teams need to configure your marketplace in Marketplacer, onboard Sellers and products, manage Orders and refunds, and oversee marketplace finance after launch.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Workstream owners","Platform users"],"sections":{"Platform Foundations and Setup":"<p>Build a shared understanding of how the marketplace is structured and how your teams access and administer the environments.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Operator, seller and customer roles</li><li>Marketplace platform and ecommerce front-end boundary</li><li>Production and Sandbox</li><li>Access, authentication, team members and permissions</li><li>Site details, branding, email and notifications</li><li>Key configuration areas and change control</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Bring the people who will administer the environments.</strong> Access and configuration knowledge should not sit with one project contact.</div>","Marketplace Structure and Commercials":"<p>Connect the product structure and financial model to the business decisions already being made.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Taxonomy, categories, prototypes, Option Types and Option Values</li><li>Brands and product-data requirements</li><li>Commission and wholesale models</li><li>Commission packages and postage treatment</li><li>Merchant fees and tax</li><li>Payments, remittance delay and payout controls</li><li>Shipping profiles, zones and rates</li></ul><p>Use representative products and seller agreements during practical exercises so the team can test real requirements.</p>","Seller, Product and Order Operations":"<p>Prepare the teams that will create sellers, connect catalogues, govern products and support fulfilment.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Seller creation, settings, access and onboarding</li><li>Product ingestion through portal, bulk, MConnect or API</li><li>Mapping, product vetting and Catalog Rules</li><li>Golden Records and duplicate-product handling</li><li>Order and seller-invoice structure</li><li>Fulfilment, partial shipments, carriers and tracking</li><li>Seller performance and operational queues</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Connection method changes the training need.</strong> A seller receiving orders through Shopify needs different daily guidance from a seller working entirely in the Seller Portal.</div>","Refunds and Marketplace Finance":"<p>Train customer service, operations and finance on the complete cancellation, return and financial workflow.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Pre-dispatch cancellation and post-dispatch return distinctions</li><li>Seller refund permissions</li><li>Return Required, returnless and denial</li><li>Refund statuses and operator finalisation</li><li>Payment-provider refund responsibility</li><li>Commission, fees, postage, tax and promotion adjustments</li><li>Remittances, payouts and reconciliation</li><li>Manual and API workflows, exceptions and monitoring</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Marketplacer financial completion is not the cash transfer.</strong> Your payment process must return money to the customer and your reconciliation must prove both records agree.</div><h3>Training completion</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Attendees can perform the tasks assigned to their role.</li><li>Open business decisions are recorded with owners.</li><li>Sandbox exercises have been completed.</li><li>Operating procedures and seller guidance are updated.</li><li>Additional internal training needs are assigned.</li></ul>"},"related":[["marketplace-architecture","Marketplace Architecture"],["configuration-overview","Configuration Overview"],["onboarding-to-launch","From Onboarding to Launch"]]},"onboarding-to-launch":{"summary":"Turn onboarding decisions and training into completed configuration, live seller and product readiness, end-to-end validation, formal go-live approval and a controlled handover to Customer Success and ongoing operations.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Project team","Launch owners"],"sections":{"Applying Decisions":"<p>Translate each approved decision into platform settings, seller terms, front-end behaviour, integration rules and operating procedures.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision</th><th>Implementation examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller commercial model</td><td>Commission package, wholesale fields, seller agreement and finance report</td></tr><tr><td>Customer return policy</td><td>Return channel, reasons, seller permissions, labels and customer communication</td></tr><tr><td>Product standard</td><td>Prototype, Catalog Rules, vetting checklist and seller guide</td></tr><tr><td>Shipping model</td><td>Profiles, zones, rates, seller access and checkout wording</td></tr><tr><td>Integration ownership</td><td>Credentials, payload mapping, webhook consumer, monitoring and fallback</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Track approval and implementation separately.</strong> A decision is not complete until it is configured, tested, communicated and verified.</div>","Completing Configuration":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Review the Marketplace Decision Register.</li><li>Complete Sandbox configuration and practical tests.</li><li>Apply approved settings to Production through change control.</li><li>Compare Sandbox and Production where they should align.</li><li>Record seller-specific exceptions.</li><li>Validate finance, tax, shipping and refund settings with the relevant owners.</li><li>Retain evidence and configuration ownership for post-launch support.</li></ul>","Testing with Sample Sellers":"<p>Use sample sellers to test the marketplace before live seller timing becomes critical.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Seller creation and permissions</li><li>Commission or wholesale configuration</li><li>Product ingestion and mapping</li><li>Product vetting and Catalog Rules</li><li>Shipping profiles and rates</li><li>Order creation and seller notification</li><li>Full and partial fulfilment</li><li>Cancellation, return and refund</li><li>Remittance and reporting</li><li>Integration failure and manual recovery</li></ul><p>Use realistic products and quantities rather than one simplified test item that cannot expose category, shipping or variant issues.</p>","Onboarding Live Sellers":"<p>Move each live seller through a controlled readiness process.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Readiness area</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Commercial</td><td>Agreement signed and approved terms configured</td></tr><tr><td>Account</td><td>Users, business details, permissions and contacts complete</td></tr><tr><td>Technology</td><td>Connection authenticated, monitored and supported</td></tr><tr><td>Catalogue</td><td>Launch range imported, mapped, approved and published correctly</td></tr><tr><td>Shipping and fulfilment</td><td>Profiles, rates, carrier, tracking and SLA tested</td></tr><tr><td>Returns and finance</td><td>Permissions, return process, refund treatment and remittance explained</td></tr><tr><td>Training</td><td>Seller can perform its required daily tasks</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","End-to-End Validation":"<p>Validate the complete marketplace across the storefront, payment provider, Marketplacer, seller system and internal teams.</p><div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Product</strong><p>Create or import, map, approve and publish.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Purchase</strong><p>Browse, cart, checkout, pay and create the Marketplacer order.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Seller operation</strong><p>Receive the invoice, dispatch and send tracking.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Exception</strong><p>Cancel before dispatch or return after dispatch.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Finance</strong><p>Complete the customer refund, seller adjustment, remittance and reporting.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">6</span><div><strong>Recovery</strong><p>Prove monitoring, incident escalation and manual fallback.</p></div></div></div><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Include exception paths in validation.</strong> Test partial, duplicate, delayed and failed scenarios before customers find them.</div><h3>Validate the commercial branch</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li><strong>Commission:</strong> verify the assigned Commission Package, rule priority, postage treatment, Merchant Fees, tax, refund adjustment and Seller remittance.</li><li><strong>Wholesale:</strong> verify website retail price, Wholesale Price, Seller RRP as reference only, Operator margin, no commission normally, refund recovery and Seller remittance.</li><li><strong>Pricing governance:</strong> confirm Seller feeds cannot overwrite protected Operator retail prices and wholesale promotional costs do not automatically create customer Sale prices.</li></ul>","Go-Live Approval":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Launch-critical decisions approved</li><li>Production configuration verified</li><li>Live sellers and products ready</li><li>Front end and payment flows passed</li><li>Integrations monitored and supported</li><li>Customer service, finance and marketplace operations ready</li><li>Incident contacts and launch coverage confirmed</li><li>Known risks documented and accepted</li><li>Rollback or containment actions understood</li><li>Executive or delegated go-live approval recorded</li></ul><p>Approve the defined launch scope. Defer sellers, categories or features that have not met readiness criteria rather than treating launch as all or nothing.</p>","Transition to Business as Usual":"<p>Move from implementation into steady-state marketplace operations once launch readiness has been approved.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Assign ongoing owners for Seller management, catalogue, Orders, customer service, finance and technology</li><li>Document the applicable Marketplacer service arrangement and Support route</li><li>Transfer open issues, configuration exceptions and known integration limitations</li><li>Confirm daily, weekly and monthly operating cadences</li><li>Schedule post-launch reviews and continuous improvement</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Post-launch support varies by agreement.</strong> Some Operators may work with a Customer Success Manager, while others use another Marketplacer service arrangement or the formal Support process.</div>"},"related":[["production-readiness","Production Readiness"],["go-live","Go-Live"],["daily-operations","Daily Marketplace Operations"]]},"how-decisions-work":{"summary":"Understand why marketplace decisions must be made before configuration, distinguish business policy from platform settings, assign ownership, manage working assumptions and dependencies, and finalise each decision at the right time.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Decision owners","Project team"],"sections":{"Why Decisions Are Required":"<p>Marketplacer provides capabilities and configuration choices, but your organisation must decide how customers, sellers and internal teams will use them. The same capability can support different marketplace models.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Customer experience and policy</li><li>Seller responsibilities and commercial terms</li><li>Catalogue and product governance</li><li>Shipping and fulfilment</li><li>Payments, refunds and remittances</li><li>Integration and data ownership</li><li>Operational monitoring and escalation</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>A capability is not a policy.</strong> Choose the business outcome first, then configure the platform and connected systems to support it.</div>","Decisions vs Platform Settings":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Business decision</th><th>Possible implementation</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Sellers may cancel before dispatch</td><td>Enable seller cancellation permission, configure reasons, train sellers and monitor cancellation rate</td></tr><tr><td>All new products require approval</td><td>Enable seller vetting, define re-vetting fields and staff the review queue</td></tr><tr><td>Operator funds a promotion</td><td>Represent the funding adjustment, approve the campaign and reconcile seller entitlement</td></tr><tr><td>Seller is paid after a 14-day delay</td><td>Configure the delay, update the agreement and test remittance eligibility</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>One decision may require several settings, procedures and integrations. One setting may also affect several business policies.</p>","Who Should Own Each Decision":"<p>Assign one accountable owner with the authority and expertise to progress the decision. Contributors can provide customer, commercial, legal, technical or operational input.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Typical owner</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Commercial model and seller terms</td><td>Commercial or marketplace lead</td></tr><tr><td>Customer service, cancellation and returns</td><td>Customer experience lead</td></tr><tr><td>Tax, remittance and reconciliation</td><td>Finance or tax lead</td></tr><tr><td>Taxonomy and product standards</td><td>Catalogue lead</td></tr><tr><td>Shipping and fulfilment</td><td>Operations or logistics lead</td></tr><tr><td>APIs, webhooks and source of truth</td><td>Technology lead</td></tr><tr><td>Restricted products and compliance</td><td>Compliance lead</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>System access does not create policy ownership.</strong> The person who can change a setting should not be the only person deciding the business rule.</div>","Working Assumptions vs Confirmed Decisions":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Working assumption</th><th>Confirmed decision</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Temporary and labelled</td><td>Approved and authoritative</td></tr><tr><td>Used to continue discovery or Sandbox work</td><td>Used for Production and operations</td></tr><tr><td>Has risks, evidence required and expiry</td><td>Has approver, effective date and change control</td></tr><tr><td>May still block selected dependent tasks</td><td>Creates implementation and verification tasks</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>A useful working position states the proposed approach, the assumptions supporting it, the risk of continuing, the activities allowed and the date it must be finalised.</p>","Dependencies Between Decisions":"<p>Marketplace decisions form a connected system.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision</th><th>Dependent decisions and work</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Commercial model</td><td>Seller agreement, price ownership, commission or wholesale configuration, refund treatment and reporting</td></tr><tr><td>Taxonomy</td><td>Prototypes, product templates, mapping, storefront navigation, tax and commission rules</td></tr><tr><td>Customer return experience</td><td>Seller permissions, return labels, shipping funding, payment refund and support process</td></tr><tr><td>Order hold</td><td>Payment capture, inventory reservation, seller notification, cancellation and SLA timing</td></tr><tr><td>Source of truth</td><td>Integration direction, manual edits, monitoring, reconciliation and fallback</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Record the earliest dependent activity so the decision receives a meaningful required-by date.</p>","When Decisions Must Be Finalised":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Before environment creation: creation-time settings such as tax model</li><li>Before seller agreement: commercial, remittance, performance and refund responsibilities</li><li>Before seller onboarding: seller settings, product standards, connection approach and training</li><li>Before development: order, payment, fulfilment, refund and data-flow decisions</li><li>Before Production configuration: approved policy and test case</li><li>Before launch: customer, seller, finance, support and incident processes</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Not every enhancement must be final for launch.</strong> Classify decisions as launch critical, required for seller onboarding, required for scale or future enhancement.</div>"},"related":[["decision-timeline","Decision Timeline"],["marketplace-decision-register","Marketplace Decision Register"],["business-operating-model","Business and Operating Model"]]},"decision-timeline":{"summary":"See the major marketplace questions that need an answer at each onboarding milestone, understand what will be blocked if they remain unresolved, and record the approved outcome in the Marketplace Decision Register.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Project manager","Decision owners","Workstream owners"],"sections":{"Understand the Decision Timeline":"\n<p>The Decision Timeline helps you answer one practical question throughout onboarding: <strong>what must we decide before the next piece of work can proceed safely?</strong></p>\n<p>It does not replace the detailed Marketplace Decisions pages. Those pages explain the available choices and implications. The timeline shows when the answer is needed, while the Marketplace Decision Register records what you approved.</p>\n<div class=\"card-grid\">\n  <article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Decision Timeline</h3><p>Shows the questions coming up, the milestone by which each answer is needed and the work that depends on it.</p></article>\n  <article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Detailed decision pages</h3><p>Explain the available models, responsibilities, trade-offs and platform implications for each decision area.</p></article>\n  <article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Marketplace Decision Register</h3><p>Records the owner, working position, final decision, rationale, approval and implementation status.</p></article>\n</div>\n<div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Use milestones rather than one project-wide deadline.</strong> A decision is due before the earliest activity that cannot proceed safely without it.</div>\n","Decision Milestones at a Glance":"\n<div class=\"process-flow\">\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Kickoff and solution design</strong><p>Confirm the marketplace scope, operating model, commercial direction and accountable owners.</p></div></div>\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Customer journey and Seller strategy</strong><p>Define how customers and Sellers will experience and operate within the marketplace.</p></div></div>\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Configuration and development</strong><p>Approve the structural, financial, shipping, access and integration decisions that shape the solution.</p></div></div>\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Seller onboarding and Product ingestion</strong><p>Give Sellers stable requirements for accounts, connections, Product data and operating responsibilities.</p></div></div>\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>End-to-End Testing</strong><p>Confirm the expected customer, Seller, integration and financial outcomes before testing begins.</p></div></div>\n  <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">6</span><div><strong>Production Readiness and Go-Live</strong><p>Approve the final launch scope, controls, decision authority and business-as-usual ownership.</p></div></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Milestone</th><th>What should be clear by this point</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>Before solution design is confirmed</td><td>Marketplace scope, customer proposition, commercial model, payment approach, launch markets and primary ownership</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Before Sandbox configuration begins</td><td>Marketplace structure, Seller defaults, Product governance, shipping, returns, Finance and access approach</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Before Seller onboarding begins</td><td>Seller proposition, commercial terms, connection methods, payout requirements, Product standards and support boundaries</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Before End-to-End Testing begins</td><td>Complete customer journey, Order flow, fulfilment, refund process, financial outcomes, integrations and test participants</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Before Production Readiness</td><td>Launch Sellers, launch Products, Production configuration, monitoring, support, containment and reconciliation controls</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Before Go-Live</td><td>Formal Go decision, activation sequence, launch authority, hypercare and business-as-usual handover</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n","Before Kickoff and Solution Design":"\n<p>These decisions establish what you are building and which teams, systems and commercial processes will be required.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision question</th><th>Required by</th><th>Why it must be answered by then</th><th>Detailed guidance</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>What customer problem will the marketplace solve, and what is included in the initial launch scope?</td><td>Before solution design is confirmed</td><td>Defines the proposition, Seller profile, assortment, customer journey and launch plan.</td><td><a href=\"?page=business-operating-model\">Business and Operating Model</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which countries, currencies, languages and regions will be supported?</td><td>Before architecture and commercial design</td><td>Affects tax, shipping, payments, content and legal requirements.</td><td><a href=\"?page=business-operating-model\">Business and Operating Model</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Will the marketplace use commission, wholesale or a mixed model?</td><td>Before Seller agreements and Finance design</td><td>Determines pricing ownership, Seller entitlement, required Product fields and financial configuration.</td><td><a href=\"?page=commercial-financial-decisions\">Commercial and Financial Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which payment provider and customer payment methods will be used?</td><td>Before checkout architecture and payment development</td><td>Affects checkout, Order creation, refunds and reconciliation.</td><td><a href=\"?page=commercial-financial-decisions\">Commercial and Financial Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Will the marketplace use MPay?</td><td>Before Seller payout onboarding begins</td><td>Affects business verification, remittance, payout readiness and Support processes.</td><td><a href=\"?page=commercial-financial-decisions\">Commercial and Financial Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Will the customer experience support multi-Seller carts?</td><td>Before storefront and Order architecture is confirmed</td><td>Affects checkout, shipping, Order splitting, customer communications and testing.</td><td><a href=\"?page=customer-experience-decisions\">Customer Experience Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Who owns the storefront, payments, integrations and marketplace operations?</td><td>Before the onboarding plan is baselined</td><td>Establishes delivery responsibilities, training needs, escalation and future operating ownership.</td><td><a href=\"?page=marketplace-operations-decisions\">Marketplace Operations Decisions</a></td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n","Before Customer Journey and Seller Strategy":"\n<p>Confirm the positions that shape the customer experience, Seller proposition and division of responsibilities.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision question</th><th>Required by</th><th>Why it must be answered by then</th><th>Detailed guidance</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>How will Seller identity appear across browse, Product detail, cart, checkout and customer communications?</td><td>Before Customer Journey Mapping is finalised</td><td>Shapes the storefront design and the customer’s understanding of who is selling and fulfilling each item.</td><td><a href=\"?page=customer-experience-decisions\">Customer Experience Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Who owns customer enquiries, cancellations, returns, refunds and complaints?</td><td>Before customer policies and service procedures are written</td><td>Prevents gaps or duplicated communication between the Operator and Sellers.</td><td><a href=\"?page=customer-experience-decisions\">Customer Experience Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>What is the ideal Seller profile and how many Sellers are required for launch?</td><td>Before Seller recruitment and qualification progress</td><td>Sets the launch pipeline, onboarding workload and assortment priorities.</td><td><a href=\"?page=seller-strategy-decisions\">Seller Strategy Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>What will the Seller proposition include?</td><td>Before Seller outreach and agreement design</td><td>Clarifies the commercial offer, support, Product onboarding and operational expectations.</td><td><a href=\"?page=seller-strategy-decisions\">Seller Strategy Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Who owns Seller recruitment, onboarding, launch approval and ongoing relationship management?</td><td>Before Seller activity begins</td><td>Separates pipeline ownership from technical onboarding and business-as-usual management.</td><td><a href=\"?page=seller-strategy-decisions\">Seller Strategy Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Who funds Promotions and discounts?</td><td>Before Promotion terms and Seller agreements are finalised</td><td>Affects customer price, Seller entitlement, commission and financial reconciliation.</td><td><a href=\"?page=commercial-financial-decisions\">Commercial and Financial Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>What performance expectations and consequences will apply to Sellers?</td><td>Before Seller agreements and launch criteria are finalised</td><td>Defines dispatch, cancellation, Product quality and corrective-action expectations.</td><td><a href=\"?page=seller-strategy-decisions\">Seller Strategy Decisions</a></td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n","Before Configuration and Development":"\n<p>These answers should be stable before the related platform settings, frontend behaviour or integrations are built.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision question</th><th>Required by</th><th>Why it must be answered by then</th><th>Detailed guidance</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>Will you use Marketplacer Global Taxonomy or your own taxonomy?</td><td>Before Categories, Prototypes, Product specifications and Mapping are designed</td><td>Determines Product structure, customer navigation, Mapping and long-term catalogue maintenance.</td><td><a href=\"?page=catalogue-decisions\">Catalogue Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Will Product Vetting be enabled, and which changes require re-review?</td><td>Before Product onboarding begins</td><td>Determines the approval workflow, monitored changes and Seller expectations.</td><td><a href=\"?page=product-governance-decisions\">Product Governance Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which Catalog Rules will be enforced?</td><td>Before representative Product testing</td><td>Defines mandatory data and the conditions a Product must meet before publication.</td><td><a href=\"?page=product-governance-decisions\">Product Governance Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Will Golden Records be used?</td><td>Before catalogue architecture and high-volume Product ingestion</td><td>Affects duplicate management, Product matching and ownership of shared versus Seller-specific data.</td><td><a href=\"?page=catalogue-decisions\">Catalogue Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Will Shipping Rules be used?</td><td>Before shipping configuration and Seller shipping requirements are finalised</td><td>Affects checkout rates, Seller responsibilities, financial outcomes and testing.</td><td><a href=\"?page=shipping-fulfilment-decisions\">Shipping and Fulfilment Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Will shipping be managed by the Operator, each Seller or a combination?</td><td>Before Seller onboarding and Shipping Profiles are configured</td><td>Defines rate ownership, zones, carriers, SLAs and ongoing maintenance.</td><td><a href=\"?page=shipping-fulfilment-decisions\">Shipping and Fulfilment Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>What tax, merchant-fee, remittance and payout controls will apply?</td><td>Before Finance Settings and expected outcomes are finalised</td><td>Determines Order calculations, refunds, Seller entitlement and reconciliation.</td><td><a href=\"?page=commercial-financial-decisions\">Commercial and Financial Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>What is the source of truth for Product content, price and stock?</td><td>Before integration configuration or Product templates are finalised</td><td>Determines update direction, correction ownership and conflict handling.</td><td><a href=\"?page=integration-data-decisions\">Integration and Data Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which Seller connection methods will be supported?</td><td>Before technical discovery and integration development</td><td>Determines Seller onboarding, authentication, data flow, monitoring and fallback requirements.</td><td><a href=\"?page=integration-data-decisions\">Integration and Data Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which Operator roles, MFA, SSO and access controls are required?</td><td>Before Production users and support access are created</td><td>Supports least-privilege access, operational coverage and account recovery.</td><td><a href=\"?page=marketplace-operations-decisions\">Marketplace Operations Decisions</a></td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n","Before Seller Onboarding and Product Ingestion":"\n<p>Give Sellers stable requirements before they prepare accounts, Product data or connected-system work.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision question</th><th>Required by</th><th>Why it must be answered by then</th><th>Detailed guidance</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>What information, agreements and approvals are required before a Seller account is created?</td><td>Before Seller onboarding begins</td><td>Prevents incomplete or commercially unapproved Sellers from progressing.</td><td><a href=\"?page=seller-strategy-decisions\">Seller Strategy Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which connection method will each Seller use?</td><td>Before technical onboarding and Product preparation</td><td>Determines the Seller’s setup, training, data ownership and test plan.</td><td><a href=\"?page=integration-data-decisions\">Integration and Data Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which Categories, Prototypes, required attributes and Variant Options apply?</td><td>Before final Product files or integrations are prepared</td><td>Provides a stable Product specification and reduces avoidable rework.</td><td><a href=\"?page=catalogue-decisions\">Catalogue Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Who controls customer-facing retail price, and which wholesale or commission fields must the Seller provide?</td><td>Before Seller Product templates and agreements are finalised</td><td>Prevents conflicting prices and incorrect Seller entitlement.</td><td><a href=\"?page=commercial-financial-decisions\">Commercial and Financial Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which Shipping Profiles, zones, rates, Carriers and dispatch SLAs apply?</td><td>Before Seller shipping setup and training</td><td>Defines checkout outcomes, fulfilment requirements and performance expectations.</td><td><a href=\"?page=shipping-fulfilment-decisions\">Shipping and Fulfilment Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Can Sellers initiate cancellations or returns?</td><td>Before Seller training and End-to-End Testing</td><td>Affects permissions, Customer Service ownership and refund procedures.</td><td><a href=\"?page=order-refund-decisions\">Order, Cancellation and Refund Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>How will Orders reach the Seller, and how will fulfilment and tracking return?</td><td>Before Seller workflow testing</td><td>Defines the connected Order lifecycle and customer communication path.</td><td><a href=\"?page=integration-data-decisions\">Integration and Data Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>What evidence is required before a Seller may launch?</td><td>Before the first Seller readiness review</td><td>Establishes an objective approval, pause and defer process.</td><td><a href=\"?page=seller-strategy-decisions\">Seller Strategy Decisions</a></td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Do not give Sellers moving requirements.</strong> If a decision is still unresolved, identify exactly what work may continue and what must wait.</div>\n","Before End-to-End Testing":"\n<p>Testing should prove approved decisions, not discover the operating model for the first time.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision question</th><th>Required by</th><th>Why it must be answered by then</th><th>Detailed guidance</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>Which Sellers, Products and customer scenarios represent the launch scope?</td><td>Before the detailed Test Matrix is finalised</td><td>Ensures testing reflects real marketplace risk and commercial models.</td><td><a href=\"?page=marketplace-operations-decisions\">Marketplace Operations Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>What are the expected commission and wholesale financial outcomes?</td><td>Before the first financial test Order</td><td>Provides the benchmark for Orders, refunds, remittance and payout.</td><td><a href=\"?page=commercial-financial-decisions\">Commercial and Financial Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which payment success, failure and uncertain-result scenarios must be tested?</td><td>Before checkout testing</td><td>Confirms customer payments and Marketplacer Orders remain reconcilable.</td><td><a href=\"?page=commercial-financial-decisions\">Commercial and Financial Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Will partial fulfilment, split Shipments or multi-Seller Order splitting apply?</td><td>Before fulfilment scenarios are prepared</td><td>Determines the required Seller, Shipment and customer communication tests.</td><td><a href=\"?page=shipping-fulfilment-decisions\">Shipping and Fulfilment Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Who completes the customer payment refund and who confirms the Seller financial adjustment?</td><td>Before cancellation and return testing</td><td>Keeps Marketplacer workflow, customer cash movement and Seller entitlement aligned.</td><td><a href=\"?page=order-refund-decisions\">Order, Cancellation and Refund Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which retry, deduplication, error-monitoring and manual fallback scenarios will be tested?</td><td>Before integration test exit</td><td>Confirms connected systems can recover without duplicate or missing records.</td><td><a href=\"?page=integration-data-decisions\">Integration and Data Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>What evidence is required, and who may approve each test stage?</td><td>Before test execution begins</td><td>Prevents incomplete or untraceable testing from being treated as accepted.</td><td><a href=\"?page=marketplace-operations-decisions\">Marketplace Operations Decisions</a></td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n","Before Production Readiness and Go-Live":"\n<p>Final launch decisions should define exactly what is being activated, how it will be controlled and who owns the marketplace once trading begins.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision question</th><th>Required by</th><th>Why it must be answered by then</th><th>Detailed guidance</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>Which Sellers, Products, features and integrations are included at launch?</td><td>Before Production Readiness</td><td>Defines the controlled launch baseline and approval scope.</td><td><a href=\"?page=business-operating-model\">Business and Operating Model</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which capabilities or defects will be deferred, and who accepts the risk?</td><td>Before the Go or No-Go review</td><td>Prevents unresolved optional work from being confused with launch-critical risk.</td><td><a href=\"?page=marketplace-operations-decisions\">Marketplace Operations Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>What Production smoke test will be completed?</td><td>Before Go-Live</td><td>Confirms the critical live path immediately after activation.</td><td><a href=\"?page=marketplace-operations-decisions\">Marketplace Operations Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>How will traffic, Sellers and Products be activated?</td><td>Before the Launch-Day Runbook is approved</td><td>Supports staged release and targeted containment.</td><td><a href=\"?page=business-operating-model\">Business and Operating Model</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Who has authority to Go, pause, contain or stop the launch?</td><td>Before Go-Live</td><td>Enables rapid and accountable decisions during live trading.</td><td><a href=\"?page=marketplace-operations-decisions\">Marketplace Operations Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>What is the smallest effective containment available for each major risk?</td><td>Before Go-Live</td><td>Allows affected Sellers, Products or integrations to be controlled without unnecessarily stopping the marketplace.</td><td><a href=\"?page=marketplace-operations-decisions\">Marketplace Operations Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Which metrics, queues and financial records will be monitored during hypercare?</td><td>Before launch</td><td>Ensures early issues are detected, assigned and reconciled.</td><td><a href=\"?page=marketplace-operations-decisions\">Marketplace Operations Decisions</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td>When does hypercare end, and who owns each process in business as usual?</td><td>Before Go-Live approval</td><td>Prevents the marketplace from depending indefinitely on the implementation team.</td><td><a href=\"?page=marketplace-operations-decisions\">Marketplace Operations Decisions</a></td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n","Manage Blocking and Deferred Decisions":"\n<p>Not every unanswered question should stop the whole onboarding programme. Classify unresolved decisions according to the work they affect.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Classification</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>Blocking</td><td>Dependent work cannot proceed safely.</td><td>Escalate and resolve before the affected activity continues.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Required soon</td><td>Initial work may proceed, but the answer is needed before the next milestone.</td><td>Assign an owner, required-by milestone and escalation point.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Conditional</td><td>The decision is needed only if a feature, Seller or model is adopted.</td><td>Record the trigger and the point at which it will be reviewed.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Deferred</td><td>The item does not affect the approved launch scope.</td><td>Move it into a controlled post-launch backlog with an owner.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Superseded</td><td>A later approved decision has replaced the earlier position.</td><td>Retain the history and link the replacement decision.</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3>Decisions that commonly become blockers</h3>\n<ul class=\"bullet-list\">\n<li>Commission, wholesale or mixed commercial model</li>\n<li>Global Taxonomy or custom taxonomy</li>\n<li>Source of truth for Product content, price and stock</li>\n<li>Seller connection and Order-delivery method</li>\n<li>Shipping Rules and shipping responsibility</li>\n<li>Product Vetting, Catalog Rules and Golden Records where applicable</li>\n<li>Customer payment refund and Seller financial-adjustment ownership</li>\n<li>MPay and Seller payout approach</li>\n<li>Launch Sellers, Products and decision authority</li>\n</ul>\n","Use the Marketplace Decision Register":"\n<p>Record every material decision in the Marketplace Decision Register so the answer remains visible after the meeting or training session in which it was discussed.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Register field</th><th>What to record</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>Decision and area</td><td>The question requiring an approved answer.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Accountable owner and approver</td><td>The person progressing the decision and the person with final authority.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Required-by milestone</td><td>The earliest activity that cannot proceed safely without the answer.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Working position</td><td>The temporary proposed answer, assumptions, risks and work allowed to continue.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Final decision and rationale</td><td>The approved position, why it was selected and where it applies.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Implementation impact</td><td>Affected settings, Sellers, documents, Products, integrations and procedures.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Testing and evidence</td><td>How the decision will be proven and where the evidence is stored.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Status and review date</td><td>Whether the decision is proposed, approved, implemented, verified or superseded.</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Approval is not the final step.</strong> A decision is complete only when it has been implemented, tested, communicated to the affected teams and reflected in current operating guidance.</div>\n<p>Use <a href=\"?page=how-decisions-work\">How Marketplace Decisions Work</a> for the decision-governance approach and <a href=\"?page=marketplace-decision-register\">Marketplace Decision Register</a> for the working record.</p>\n"},"related":[["how-decisions-work","How Marketplace Decisions Work"],["marketplace-decision-register","Marketplace Decision Register"],["business-operating-model","Business and Operating Model"],["production-readiness","Production Readiness"]]},"business-operating-model":{"summary":"Define how the marketplace earns revenue, divides responsibilities between you and sellers, owns the customer relationship, provides support, funds marketplace activity and limits the initial launch scope.","audience":["Marketplace leadership","Commercial","Finance","Operations"],"sections":{"Commission vs Wholesale":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>How it works</th><th>Primary decisions</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Commission</td><td>Seller sets or supplies the selling price and you earn an agreed percentage or fee</td><td>Commission basis, packages, postage, fees, promotions and refunds</td></tr><tr><td>Wholesale</td><td>Seller supplies a wholesale cost and you control the customer-facing retail price</td><td>Price ownership, margin floor, promotions, cost changes and refunds</td></tr><tr><td>Hybrid</td><td>Different sellers or variants use different models</td><td>Clear eligibility, configuration, reporting and seller communication</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Choose the model before contracting sellers.</strong> The model changes price ownership, financial calculation, promotion funding and seller reporting.</div>","Operator vs Seller Responsibilities":"<p>Define responsibilities at a process level rather than relying on a general statement that the seller fulfils orders.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Activity</th><th>Possible owner</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Customer acquisition and checkout</td><td>You</td></tr><tr><td>Product source content</td><td>Seller, subject to your standards</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplace category and approval</td><td>You</td></tr><tr><td>Price and inventory</td><td>Seller under commission, or divided under wholesale</td></tr><tr><td>Fulfilment and tracking</td><td>Seller or fulfilment partner</td></tr><tr><td>Customer communication</td><td>Usually you, with seller input</td></tr><tr><td>Return assessment</td><td>Seller, you or shared</td></tr><tr><td>Payment refund</td><td>You through your payment process</td></tr><tr><td>Remittance and reconciliation</td><td>You and finance providers</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Reflect responsibilities in seller agreements, training, permissions, operational procedures and escalation paths.</p>","Customer Relationship Ownership":"<p>Decide who customers believe they are buying from and who remains accountable when several sellers contribute to one order.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Marketplace branding and seller visibility</li><li>Terms and customer policies</li><li>Customer data and consent</li><li>Order confirmation and notifications</li><li>Customer support channel</li><li>Complaint and escalation ownership</li><li>Goodwill and policy exception authority</li><li>Seller direct-contact boundaries</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Seller input does not require seller-owned customer service.</strong> You can own the customer conversation while the seller supplies fulfilment or product evidence.</div>","Marketplace Support Model":"<div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Operator-led</h3><p>Your support team receives and coordinates all marketplace enquiries.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Dedicated marketplace team</h3><p>A specialist team supports marketplace orders while first-party support remains separate.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Shared</h3><p>Your team owns the case and sellers respond to approved operational questions.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Seller-direct</h3><p>Customers contact sellers for selected enquiry types under strict policy and visibility controls.</p></article></div><p>Define first-line owner, resolution owner, response SLA, final authority and customer communication for each enquiry type.</p>","Marketplace-Funded vs Seller-Funded Activity":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Activity</th><th>Funding decisions</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Customer discount</td><td>Operator, seller, shared or partner funded</td></tr><tr><td>Free shipping</td><td>Customer benefit, seller entitlement and carrier cost allocation</td></tr><tr><td>Return shipping</td><td>Reason-based customer, seller, operator or carrier responsibility</td></tr><tr><td>Goodwill</td><td>Approval limits and whether seller entitlement changes</td></tr><tr><td>Chargeback</td><td>Responsibility by fraud, fulfilment or service reason</td></tr><tr><td>Catalogue assistance</td><td>Included onboarding support or paid/limited service</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Separate the customer-facing benefit from the seller and finance allocation behind it.</p>","Initial Launch Scope":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Countries, regions and currencies</li><li>Customer segments and channels</li><li>Categories and restricted products</li><li>Named launch sellers</li><li>Launch product range</li><li>Shipping services</li><li>Payment methods</li><li>Customer support hours</li><li>Integration scope</li><li>Features deferred to a later phase</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Launch the scope you can operate reliably.</strong> A smaller proven marketplace creates a stronger base for expansion than a broad launch with unresolved customer and financial processes.</div>"},"related":[["commercial-financial-decisions","Commercial and Financial Decisions"],["customer-experience-decisions","Customer Experience Decisions"],["seller-strategy-decisions","Seller Strategy Decisions"]]},"customer-experience-decisions":{"summary":"Define how sellers, products, deliveries, cancellations, returns, refunds and support appear to customers across a multi-seller marketplace.","audience":["Customer experience","Ecommerce","Customer service","Operations"],"sections":{"Seller Identity":"<p>Decide where customers see the seller and what information is presented.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Product page seller name</li><li>Cart and checkout seller grouping</li><li>Order confirmation and history</li><li>Shipment and tracking updates</li><li>Return instructions</li><li>Seller rating or profile</li><li>Terms and policy wording</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Use seller visibility consistently.</strong> Set clear Seller and fulfilment expectations throughout the customer journey.</div>","Multi-Seller Cart":"<p>A customer may buy from several sellers in one checkout. Define how the cart groups items, calculates shipping, applies promotions and explains that fulfilment may occur separately.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Decision</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Grouping</td><td>By seller, delivery group, product type or one combined list</td></tr><tr><td>Shipping</td><td>Separate seller charges or marketplace-wide benefit</td></tr><tr><td>Thresholds</td><td>Whole cart or per seller</td></tr><tr><td>Promotions</td><td>Line-item allocation and funding across sellers</td></tr><tr><td>Unavailable item</td><td>Block the cart, remove item or continue with remaining items</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","Split Shipments":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Show which items are in each shipment.</li><li>Use seller, carrier, tracking and dispatch date accurately.</li><li>Represent items still preparing, cancelled or delayed.</li><li>Allow customer service to search by customer order and seller invoice.</li><li>Avoid marking the complete order dispatched when only one seller has fulfilled.</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>One checkout does not mean one parcel.</strong> Prepare customers for multiple deliveries without making the marketplace feel fragmented.</div>","Delivery Promises":"<p>Define how dispatch lead time and carrier transit combine into a customer promise.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Standard and seller-specific dispatch SLAs</li><li>Business days, cut-offs and seller closures</li><li>Metro, regional, remote and international estimates</li><li>Bulky, made-to-order and pre-order products</li><li>Tracking requirements</li><li>Delay communication and cancellation option</li></ul><p>Use the system that can maintain the estimate accurately and ensure the promise remains consistent from product page through order history.</p>","Cancellation Experience":"<p>Decide how customers request pre-dispatch cancellation and how you avoid promising an outcome after fulfilment has begun.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Self-service or assisted request</li><li>Eligibility status and order hold</li><li>Partial item or quantity cancellation</li><li>Seller confirmation</li><li>Shipping and promotion recalculation</li><li>Payment void or refund</li><li>Declined cancellation and return alternative</li></ul>","Return Experience":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Primary request channel</li><li>Return eligibility and evidence</li><li>Return Required or returnless</li><li>Label, collection or customer-arranged shipping</li><li>Return destination</li><li>Seller assessment and operator override</li><li>Customer-visible statuses</li><li>Deadlines and reminders</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Use one clear customer pathway.</strong> Internal seller, Marketplacer and payment steps can remain behind the service experience.</div>","Refund Experience":"<p>Define customer wording for each event rather than using one broad “refunded” status.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Event</th><th>Customer meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Refund approved</td><td>The request has been accepted</td></tr><tr><td>Refund submitted</td><td>The payment provider has received the instruction</td></tr><tr><td>Refund processing</td><td>The provider is returning funds</td></tr><tr><td>Refund completed</td><td>The customer should have received or can trace the funds</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Refund amount and components</li><li>Original payment method</li><li>Expected provider timeframe</li><li>Partial refund visibility</li><li>Failed refund escalation</li><li>Customer confirmation</li></ul>","Customer Service Channels":"<p>Choose the primary channels and define how marketplace cases are identified and routed.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Customer account or return portal</li><li>Email, form, chat and phone</li><li>Service hours and urgent escalation</li><li>Seller contact rules</li><li>Case records and internal notes</li><li>Financial authority limits</li><li>Handoffs to finance, technology, carrier or compliance</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>The customer should not need to understand your system architecture.</strong> Coordinate the seller and provider investigation behind one accountable support journey.</div>"},"related":[["customer-journey-mapping","Customer Journey Mapping"],["order-refund-decisions","Order, Cancellation and Refund Decisions"],["marketplace-operations-decisions","Marketplace Operations Decisions"]]},"seller-strategy-decisions":{"summary":"Define the sellers you want, the launch and post-launch recruitment plan, agreement and onboarding ownership, product assistance, training and performance consequences.","audience":["Marketplace leadership","Seller team","Commercial","Operations"],"sections":{"Ideal Seller Profile":"<p>Describe the sellers most likely to strengthen the customer proposition and operate successfully.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Assessment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Range</td><td>Category fit, brands, exclusivity and product quality</td></tr><tr><td>Customer value</td><td>Demand, price, availability and delivery proposition</td></tr><tr><td>Technology</td><td>Platform, identifiers, data quality and integration capability</td></tr><tr><td>Operations</td><td>Inventory, dispatch, tracking, returns and support</td></tr><tr><td>Commercial</td><td>Margin, commission tolerance, promotions and agreement readiness</td></tr><tr><td>Risk</td><td>Compliance, authenticity, financial and reputational exposure</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Use the profile to prioritise outreach and to decline sellers who would consume disproportionate onboarding or support capacity.</p>","Launch Seller Targets":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Named sellers and current stage</li><li>Category and product contribution</li><li>Target connection method</li><li>Estimated catalogue size</li><li>Commercial and legal readiness</li><li>Technical contact and responsiveness</li><li>Testing commitment</li><li>Fallback if the seller misses launch</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Prefer ready and collaborative launch sellers.</strong> A smaller group that responds quickly and provides usable product data is more valuable than a large unprepared list.</div>","Post-Launch Recruitment":"<p>Create a pipeline linked to customer demand, category gaps and onboarding capacity.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Priority categories and brands</li><li>Monthly or quarterly recruitment target</li><li>Lead sources and qualification criteria</li><li>Pipeline stages and conversion owner</li><li>Connection-method mix</li><li>Expected onboarding capacity</li><li>Commercial and operational review after launch</li></ul><p>Use early seller and customer data to refine the ideal profile rather than continuing the launch assumptions indefinitely.</p>","Seller Agreement":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Commercial model, rates and fees</li><li>Price, promotion and shipping responsibilities</li><li>Product standards and restricted products</li><li>Customer service, cancellation and returns</li><li>Refund, chargeback and financial recovery</li><li>Dispatch, tracking and response SLAs</li><li>Data, privacy and integration obligations</li><li>Suspension, termination and change process</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Complete core agreement positions before onboarding.</strong> Configuration and seller training should match the terms the seller is being asked to accept.</div>","Seller Onboarding Owner":"<p>Define ownership from recruitment through launch.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Accountability</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Recruitment</td><td>Outreach, qualification and pipeline progression</td></tr><tr><td>Commercial conversion</td><td>Proposal, negotiation and signed agreement</td></tr><tr><td>Onboarding handoff</td><td>Complete seller information, scope and contacts</td></tr><tr><td>Platform onboarding</td><td>Account, settings, connection, products, training and testing</td></tr><tr><td>Launch approval</td><td>Readiness evidence and go-live decision</td></tr><tr><td>Ongoing management</td><td>Performance, growth, support and commercial relationship</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Where recruitment is a contracted service, document the exact scope.</strong> Seller outreach and pipeline conversion should not become an assumed responsibility of the implementation team.</div>","Product Onboarding Assistance":"<p>Decide what help you provide and when seller ownership begins.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Support option</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Guidance only</td><td>Templates, standards, training and office hours</td></tr><tr><td>Operator-assisted launch</td><td>Initial file review, mapping and limited remediation</td></tr><tr><td>Managed onboarding</td><td>Operator performs defined catalogue work under an approved scope</td></tr><tr><td>Partner service</td><td>Integration or data partner supports transformation and upload</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Products and rounds included</li><li>Mapping and enrichment included</li><li>Image or compliance work included</li><li>Correction owner</li><li>Completion date</li><li>Ongoing maintenance owner</li><li>Out-of-scope requests and escalation</li></ul>","Seller Training":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Portal access and security</li><li>Product source of truth and correction method</li><li>Order, fulfilment and tracking process</li><li>Cancellation and return responsibilities</li><li>Customer communication boundaries</li><li>Remittance and reporting</li><li>Support route and incident escalation</li><li>Readiness exercise or test order</li></ul><p>Adapt training to the connection method and the tasks the seller will actually perform.</p>","Performance Enforcement":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Possible response</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Early trend</td><td>Coaching and evidence review</td></tr><tr><td>Repeated breach</td><td>Formal warning and corrective action plan</td></tr><tr><td>Material customer impact</td><td>Increased vetting, catalogue restriction or manual payout approval</td></tr><tr><td>Severe or persistent risk</td><td>Seller suspension or termination review</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Define thresholds, minimum sample size, approved exclusions, decision authority and how commercial importance is separated from operational risk.</p>"},"related":[["seller-strategy-session","Seller Strategy"],["seller-lifecycle","Seller Lifecycle"],["seller-performance","Seller Performance"]]},"commercial-financial-decisions":{"summary":"Define how you earn revenue, calculate seller charges, manage wholesale margin, apply tax, fund promotions, delay and approve remittances, treat refunds and allocate responsibility for chargebacks.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Commercial","Finance and tax","Operations"],"sections":{"Commission Rates":"<p>Confirm the rate and the amount to which it applies. A percentage is incomplete until product price, promotional price, postage, tax and other eligible components are defined.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Default rate</li><li>Category, Brand or price-tier variation</li><li>Seller-specific negotiation authority</li><li>Gross or net calculation basis</li><li>Promotion and refund treatment</li><li>Effective dates and existing-order treatment</li><li>Seller communication and testing</li></ul><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Example</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Customer product price</td><td>$100</td></tr><tr><td>Commission at 15%</td><td>$15</td></tr><tr><td>Seller amount before other charges</td><td>$85</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Control variation.</strong> Create different rates only where the commercial value outweighs configuration, support and reconciliation complexity.</div>","Commission Packages":"<p>Use packages to group default and custom commission rules and assign the correct commercial structure to each seller.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Default package and default rate</li><li>Category, Brand and price-tier rules</li><li>Rule priority</li><li>Commission on postage</li><li>Seller assignments</li><li>Scheduled start or end dates</li><li>Package naming and register</li><li>Sandbox and Production tests</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>A broad rule can hide a more specific rule.</strong> Test products that match several conditions and document the expected priority.</div>","Commission on Postage":"<p>Decide whether line-item postage forms part of the commissionable value.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Include postage when</th><th>Exclude postage when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Commercial terms use total transaction value</td><td>Seller bears carrier cost and terms exclude shipping</td></tr><tr><td>You want to prevent value shifting into postage</td><td>Product commission already covers marketplace service</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplace supports the complete delivery transaction</td><td>Seller shipping economics are sensitive</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Paid and free shipping</li><li>Partial order and multi-item allocation</li><li>Product-only versus postage refund</li><li>Commission reversal or retention</li><li>Tax and seller agreement wording</li></ul>","Merchant Fees":"<p>Define any fixed, percentage or combined seller-side transaction fee and the cost it is intended to recover.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Fee amount and calculation base</li><li>Sellers included or exempt</li><li>Tax</li><li>Pre-dispatch and post-dispatch refund treatment</li><li>Difference from customer payment surcharges</li><li>Reporting and reconciliation</li><li>Waiver authority</li></ul><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Illustrative component</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Base fee</td><td>$0.30</td></tr><tr><td>Percentage fee on $100 at 1.5%</td><td>$1.50</td></tr><tr><td>Total merchant fee</td><td>$1.80</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","Wholesale Margin":"<p>Under wholesale, the Seller amount is based on the approved Variant-level Wholesale Price and the Operator controls or approves the customer-facing website retail price. Commission does not normally apply to a wholesale-priced Variant.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Typical owner</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Website retail price</td><td>Amount charged to the customer, including any active customer Sale price.</td><td>Operator, merchandising or approved pricing system.</td></tr><tr><td>Wholesale Price</td><td>Starting amount owed to the Seller for the wholesale Variant.</td><td>Seller or authorised Operator under the supplier agreement.</td></tr><tr><td>Seller RRP</td><td>Reference retail value for merchandising or reporting. It may differ from the website retail price.</td><td>Seller, subject to Operator governance.</td></tr><tr><td>Wholesale promotional price</td><td>Temporary supplier cost during approved dates. It does not automatically change the customer price.</td><td>Seller or authorised Operator under campaign governance.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Decisions to record</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Retail-price owner and approval process.</li><li>Wholesale-cost owner, notice period and source of truth.</li><li>Minimum and target margin.</li><li>Seller RRP use and visibility.</li><li>Customer Sale-price and wholesale promotional-cost coordination.</li><li>Promotion funding and effective dates.</li><li>Refund, post-payout recovery and negative-balance treatment.</li><li>Bulk update, integration overwrite and validation controls.</li></ul><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Standard</th><th>Operator-funded customer sale</th><th>Supplier-supported sale</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Website retail price</td><td>$100</td><td>$85</td><td>$85</td></tr><tr><td>Effective Wholesale Price</td><td>$70</td><td>$70</td><td>$60</td></tr><tr><td>Gross product margin</td><td>$30</td><td>$15</td><td>$25</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Protect Operator-controlled retail pricing.</strong> Validate price below cost, stale cost, tax mismatch, promotion dates and Seller-feed overwrites before publication.</div>","Tax Treatment":"<p>Confirm the marketplace tax model and the source and priority of rates for item, category, advert, variant, postage, commission and merchant fees.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Tax-inclusive or tax-exclusive platform model</li><li>Default and override rates</li><li>Seller tax information and validation</li><li>Postage, commission and fee tax</li><li>Withholding or marketplace-facilitator responsibilities</li><li>Integration payloads</li><li>Refund and credit treatment</li><li>Qualified tax advice for each jurisdiction</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Set one authoritative tax approach.</strong> Document the hierarchy and reconciliation process when several systems can supply competing rates.</div>","Promotion Funding":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Funding model</th><th>Seller outcome</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Marketplace funded</td><td>You absorb the approved discount while preserving the agreed seller entitlement</td></tr><tr><td>Seller funded</td><td>Seller eligible amount is reduced by the approved contribution</td></tr><tr><td>Shared</td><td>Operator and seller contributions are allocated by percentage or fixed amount</td></tr><tr><td>Partner funded</td><td>Another party funds the discount under a documented reconciliation process</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Eligible sellers, products and dates</li><li>Customer discount and line-item allocation</li><li>Commission or wholesale basis</li><li>Shipping promotion</li><li>Tax</li><li>Refund and minimum-spend treatment</li><li>Approvals and campaign reconciliation</li></ul>","Remittance Delay":"<p>Set the time a completed seller invoice waits before becoming eligible for remittance processing.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Global delay and seller exceptions</li><li>Event that starts the delay</li><li>Calendar or business days</li><li>Relationship to delivery and return window</li><li>Seller cash-flow impact</li><li>Change and notice process</li><li>Difference between delay, approval, payout frequency and settlement</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Eligibility is not settlement.</strong> An invoice may still require approval, positive balance and payout-provider processing after the delay.</div>","Automatic Payout Approval":"<p>Decide whether eligible remittances proceed automatically or wait for manual approval.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Manual approval suits</th><th>Automatic approval suits</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>New marketplace or high-risk sellers</td><td>Stable configuration and proven finance controls</td></tr><tr><td>Manual reconciliation or low seller count</td><td>Reliable refunds, monitoring and seller verification</td></tr><tr><td>Commercial disputes or probation</td><td>Routine high-volume payouts where review adds little value</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Seller eligibility and probation</li><li>Verified payout account</li><li>Negative balance and refund exposure</li><li>Pause conditions</li><li>Approval authority</li><li>Monitoring and reconciliation</li></ul>","Refund Treatment":"<p>Decide the customer refund and the seller/operator financial allocation separately.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Decision</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Item</td><td>Customer amount and seller or operator funding</td></tr><tr><td>Postage</td><td>Original shipping refund and seller entitlement</td></tr><tr><td>Commission</td><td>Full, partial or retained</td></tr><tr><td>Merchant fee</td><td>Fixed and percentage reversal</td></tr><tr><td>Wholesale</td><td>Seller liability and operator margin reversal</td></tr><tr><td>Promotion</td><td>Seller and operator contributions</td></tr><tr><td>Tax</td><td>Product, postage, fee and commission adjustments</td></tr><tr><td>After payout</td><td>Future offset, negative balance, reserve or repayment</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Marketplace finalisation and cash refund are separate.</strong> Reconcile the Marketplacer record with the payment-provider transaction.</div>","Chargeback Responsibility":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>First team receiving the dispute</li><li>Evidence owner and deadline</li><li>Seller liability by fulfilment or product reason</li><li>Operator liability by payment or service reason</li><li>Disputed amount and provider fee</li><li>Multi-seller allocation</li><li>Remittance hold, reserve or post-payout recovery</li><li>Customer service coordination and duplicate-refund prevention</li><li>Reporting, root cause and seller consequence</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Put chargeback allocation in seller terms.</strong> Define responsibility before the first live dispute, not after the seller has already been paid.</div>"},"related":[["commission-packages","Commission Packages"],["tax","Tax"],["remittances","Remittances"]]},"catalogue-decisions":{"summary":"Define the taxonomy, category depth, Brands, attributes, variants, product standards, source-of-truth rules, duplicate strategy, Golden Records approach and catalogue ownership needed to scale seller product data.","audience":["Catalogue lead","Ecommerce","Seller onboarding","Technology"],"sections":{"Global vs Custom Taxonomy":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Approach</th><th>Use when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Global Taxonomy</td><td>You need a scalable starting structure, broad coverage and predefined attributes</td></tr><tr><td>Custom taxonomy</td><td>You operate a specialist vertical, regulatory classification or mature internal product model</td></tr><tr><td>Hybrid</td><td>You want an established base with selected local naming, categories or attributes</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Launch branches and future scope</li><li>Customer-facing terminology</li><li>Front-end collections versus backend classification</li><li>Prototype and attribute coverage</li><li>Seller source-category mapping</li><li>Change governance</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Choose the approach before large product imports.</strong> Restructuring becomes harder once products, mappings, rules and front-end links depend on the hierarchy.</div>","Category Depth":"<p>Use categories for stable product classes and attributes for characteristics customers filter or compare.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Use a category when</th><th>Use an attribute when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>The distinction changes product type, prototype, compliance, tax or commission</td><td>The distinction describes age, material, form, size, preference or feature</td></tr><tr><td>Customers recognise a stable browse group</td><td>The product can have several applicable characteristics</td></tr><tr><td>Enough products justify a lasting leaf</td><td>A new category would create thin or repetitive branches</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Products belong in the lowest relevant category.</strong> Keep the permanent taxonomy stable and use ecommerce merchandising for temporary campaigns.</div>","Brand Requirements":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Mandatory, category-specific or optional Brand</li><li>Approved Unbranded or Generic treatment</li><li>Brand naming and normalisation</li><li>New Brand request and evidence</li><li>Private-label rules</li><li>Manufacturer versus consumer Brand</li><li>Duplicate and merge process</li><li>Brand impact on Golden Records, commission and promotions</li></ul><p>Control the Brand register centrally while allowing sellers to request additions through an approved process.</p>","Required Attributes":"<p>Use Advert Option Types for shared product information and Variant Option Types for buyer-selectable choices.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Customer or operational purpose for every field</li><li>Product-level or variant-level placement</li><li>Required or optional status</li><li>Controlled, single-select, multi-select or free-text input</li><li>Accepted Option Values and mapping</li><li>Front-end display or filter use</li><li>Compliance and integration needs</li><li>Owner and change process</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Every required field adds onboarding effort.</strong> Require the minimum needed to sell, govern and find the product accurately; add enrichment as catalogue maturity improves.</div>","Variant Modelling":"<p>Create a variant when the customer choice changes the SKU, barcode, price, stock, image, shipping or fulfilment record.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Core parent product identity</li><li>Buyer-selectable attributes</li><li>Valid combinations only</li><li>Stable SKU, barcode and external IDs</li><li>Variant price and inventory</li><li>Variant image where needed</li><li>Variant shipping profile and dimensions</li><li>Consistent modelling across sellers</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Model genuine size and colour choices as Variants.</strong> Also avoid grouping unrelated products as variants simply because they share a Brand or collection.</div>","Product Data Standards":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Minimum standard</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Identity</td><td>Clear title, approved Brand, category and stable identifiers</td></tr><tr><td>Content</td><td>Accurate description, specifications and included items</td></tr><tr><td>Images</td><td>Representative, accessible and marketplace-appropriate media</td></tr><tr><td>Variants</td><td>Correct choices, SKUs, barcodes, price and stock</td></tr><tr><td>Shipping</td><td>Profile, weight, dimensions and restrictions</td></tr><tr><td>Compliance</td><td>Required warnings, ingredients, evidence or registration</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Publish seller guidance with examples, accepted formats, rejection reasons and the place where integrated sellers must correct source data.</p>","Source of Truth":"<p>Assign an authoritative system and owner by field rather than by whole product.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Possible source</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Price and inventory</td><td>Seller ecommerce, ERP or Marketplacer</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplace category and Brand</td><td>Marketplacer</td></tr><tr><td>Source content and images</td><td>Seller PIM or ecommerce</td></tr><tr><td>Golden content</td><td>Central Product Database or catalogue team</td></tr><tr><td>Compliance approval</td><td>Compliance process</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Sync direction and frequency</li><li>Marketplace override</li><li>Conflict priority</li><li>Manual edit overwrite behaviour</li><li>Audit history</li><li>Change of source process</li></ul>","Duplicate Product Strategy":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Separate listings suit</th><th>Consolidated experience suits</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Handmade, used, custom, bundled or condition-specific products</td><td>Standard branded products with reliable identifiers</td></tr><tr><td>Seller-specific content or service</td><td>Customers comparing price, stock or delivery across sellers</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Matching identifiers and evidence</li><li>Pack size, model, colour and condition safeguards</li><li>Missing identifier process</li><li>Category-specific policy</li><li>Front-end offer experience</li><li>Duplicate review and remediation</li></ul>","Golden Records":"<p>Use Golden Records to separate shared product identity and content from seller-specific offers such as price, stock and shipping.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Enablement timing</li><li>Automatic or manual matching</li><li>Reliable barcode or model criteria</li><li>Golden content source by field</li><li>Seller update behaviour</li><li>Merge authority and reversibility</li><li>False-match prevention</li><li>Front-end support for multiple offers</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Enable automatic consolidation after identifiers and governance are reliable.</strong> Incorrect matches can combine products that differ in pack size, model, formulation or compatibility.</div>","Catalogue Ownership":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Responsibility</th><th>Owner to assign</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Taxonomy and prototypes</td><td>Catalogue or product-data lead</td></tr><tr><td>Brands and Option Values</td><td>Brand or attribute owner</td></tr><tr><td>Seller source data</td><td>Seller</td></tr><tr><td>Mapping and remediation</td><td>Catalogue operations</td></tr><tr><td>Product vetting and audits</td><td>Product governance team</td></tr><tr><td>Golden Records</td><td>Central catalogue owner</td></tr><tr><td>Integrations and transformations</td><td>Technology</td></tr><tr><td>Restricted products and compliance</td><td>Compliance</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Daily exception queues</li><li>Weekly mapping and vetting review</li><li>Monthly quality reporting</li><li>Quarterly taxonomy and standards review</li><li>Structural change control and seller communication</li></ul>"},"related":[["global-taxonomy","Global Taxonomy"],["product-model","Product Model"],["golden-records","Golden Records and Central Product Database"]]},"product-governance-decisions":{"summary":"Define how products qualify for publication, which sellers require vetting, which changes trigger reapproval, how Catalog Rules and rejection standards work, and how restricted products, compliance and content ownership are governed.","audience":["Catalogue and product data","Seller onboarding","Compliance","Operations"],"sections":{"Auto-Publish vs Product Vetting":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Auto-publish</th><th>Product vetting</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Faster publication after mapping and automated validation</td><td>Manual approval before publication</td></tr><tr><td>Best for trusted sellers, low-risk categories and strong data</td><td>Best for new, high-risk, regulated or inconsistent sellers</td></tr><tr><td>Requires strong Catalog Rules and live audits</td><td>Requires review capacity and consistent reviewer standards</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>A hybrid model can require vetting during seller probation, for selected categories or after a performance issue while allowing trusted low-risk products to publish automatically.</p><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Choose the default and the exception process.</strong> Define who can change a seller from vetting to auto-publish and what evidence supports the decision.</div>","Seller Vetting Requirements":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Default requirement for new sellers</li><li>Categories requiring permanent specialist review</li><li>Probation period or product-volume threshold</li><li>Quality, rejection and compliance criteria for auto-publish</li><li>Connection-method considerations</li><li>Review owner and SLA</li><li>Seller communication</li><li>Conditions that restore mandatory vetting</li></ul><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Lower risk evidence</th><th>Higher risk evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Stable integration, complete data and low rejection</td><td>New connection, poor data or high rejection</td></tr><tr><td>Reliable identifiers and approved categories</td><td>Missing identifiers or inconsistent mapping</td></tr><tr><td>No compliance incidents</td><td>Restricted-product or claim concerns</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","Re-Vetting Triggers":"<p>Monitor high-impact fields so an approved product cannot change materially without renewed review.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Usually re-vet</th><th>Usually no full re-vet</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Title, category, Brand, description, images and compliance claims</td><td>Routine inventory updates</td></tr><tr><td>Ingredients, warnings, barcode, product type or variant structure</td><td>Non-customer-facing internal references</td></tr><tr><td>Shipping classification or other risk-bearing attributes</td><td>Approved operational metadata</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Whether the live version remains visible</li><li>Source-system overwrite behaviour</li><li>Priority for safety, price and identity changes</li><li>Seller notification</li><li>Several updates while review is pending</li><li>Testing for portal and integrated sellers</li></ul>","Catalog Rules":"<p>Use Catalog Rules for objective, repeatable validation before publication or manual review.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Rule example</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Title present</td><td>Prevent blank products</td></tr><tr><td>Description length</td><td>Require useful content</td></tr><tr><td>Image present</td><td>Prevent image-free listings</td></tr><tr><td>SKU present and barcode unique</td><td>Protect operations and matching</td></tr><tr><td>Weight and shipping profile present</td><td>Support checkout calculation</td></tr><tr><td>Title does not contain prohibited phrase</td><td>Enforce content policy</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Marketplace-wide and category-specific rules</li><li>Blocking, warning or audit outcome</li><li>Actionable seller error message</li><li>Sandbox test and failure-volume review</li><li>Communication before enforcement</li><li>Owner, effective date and review date</li><li>Impact on existing live products</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Mapping, Catalog Rules and product vetting solve different problems.</strong> Use the right combination rather than asking one control to perform every governance task.</div>","Rejection Standards":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Standard reasons for identity, category, content, image, price, shipping and compliance issues</li><li>Specific instructions showing what the seller must change</li><li>Severity: correction, specialist review, prohibited or evidence required</li><li>When reviewers may correct minor issues directly</li><li>Source-of-truth location for integrated sellers</li><li>Seller dispute and escalation</li><li>Review and re-review SLA</li><li>Reviewer calibration and quality audit</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Avoid vague rejection comments.</strong> “Add a valid shipping weight in your source system” is actionable; “bad data” is not.</div>","Restricted Products":"<p>Maintain a controlled register of prohibited, approval-only, evidence-required, customer-restricted and shipping-restricted product classes.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Legal, payment, carrier, insurance and marketplace restrictions</li><li>Jurisdiction and category scope</li><li>Required evidence and approver</li><li>Customer and shipping controls</li><li>Detection through rules, vetting and audits</li><li>Immediate takedown and order impact</li><li>Seller consequence and prevention of reimport</li><li>Recall and regulatory escalation</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Build an enforcement process, not only a policy list.</strong> Assign who can remove a live product, identify affected customers and stop the source integration from republishing it.</div>","Compliance Information":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller</td><td>Business registration, licence, insurance and authorised-distributor evidence</td></tr><tr><td>Product</td><td>Ingredients, warnings, registration, certification and country of origin</td></tr><tr><td>Variant or batch</td><td>Pack-specific information, expiry or batch documentation</td></tr><tr><td>Customer-facing</td><td>Information that must appear on the product page or in instructions</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Mandatory structured fields</li><li>Document issuer and verification</li><li>Validity and expiry monitoring</li><li>Claims requiring evidence</li><li>Renewed review after formulation, warning or certification changes</li><li>Recall readiness and ownership</li></ul>","Content Responsibilities":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Responsibility</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller-managed</td><td>Seller creates and maintains source content; you set standards and approve or audit</td></tr><tr><td>Operator-assisted</td><td>You support a defined launch range and transfer ongoing ownership</td></tr><tr><td>Operator-managed</td><td>You maintain customer-facing content under a resourced commercial scope</td></tr><tr><td>Golden Record</td><td>Central team owns shared content; sellers own offer data</td></tr><tr><td>Enrichment provider</td><td>Third party supplies approved fields under clear licensing and quality rules</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Create, approve, maintain and source-of-truth owner by field</li><li>Authority to edit price, claims and compliance data</li><li>Integrated-source correction path</li><li>Initial assistance limits</li><li>Ongoing maintenance and audits</li><li>Seller agreement responsibilities and liability</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Approval does not transfer seller responsibility.</strong> Sellers remain accountable for accurate and lawful source information while you retain publication and takedown authority.</div>"},"related":[["product-vetting","Product Vetting"],["catalog-rules","Catalog Rules"],["catalogue-quality","Catalogue Quality Operations"]]},"shipping-fulfilment-decisions":{"summary":"Define shipping ownership, profiles, zones, rates, free-shipping funding, bulky and international treatment, carriers, tracking, dispatch SLAs and partial fulfilment.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Logistics","Seller onboarding","Technology"],"sections":{"Operator-Managed vs Seller-Managed Shipping":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Operator-managed</th><th>Seller-managed</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>You define rates and zones for a consistent proposition</td><td>Sellers maintain rates reflecting their own origins and carrier costs</td></tr><tr><td>Simpler checkout and seller guidance</td><td>Greater flexibility for varied fulfilment models</td></tr><tr><td>You carry maintenance and exception workload</td><td>Requires seller training, audits and consistency controls</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>A hybrid model can use standard marketplace rules with approved seller, bulky or international exceptions.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Settings sellers may access</li><li>Rate-change approval and notice</li><li>Who bears checkout versus carrier differences</li><li>Customer wording and audit process</li><li>Seller capability criteria</li></ul>","Shipping Profiles":"<p>A profile classifies a variant into a shipping treatment such as Standard, Express, Big and Bulky, Refrigerated or Fragile.</p><div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Variant</strong><p>Product and variant data identifies the shipping treatment.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Profile</strong><p>The approved profile links the variant to relevant rules.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Zone</strong><p>The customer address selects a geographic area.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Rate</strong><p>The matching service and customer charge are returned.</p></div></div></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Controlled profile list and definition</li><li>Variant-level assignment</li><li>Default or missing-profile outcome</li><li>Weight and dimensions required</li><li>Assignment through portal, bulk, mapping or integration</li><li>Profile audits and change control</li></ul>","Zones and Rates":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Countries, states, regions or postcode groups</li><li>Complete and non-conflicting coverage</li><li>Flat, per-item, quantity, profile or carrier-calculated rate</li><li>Customer-friendly service name</li><li>Per-seller and multi-product combination</li><li>Tax, handling and subsidy components</li><li>No-valid-rate outcome</li><li>Boundary and unsupported-address tests</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Escalate unmatched values rather than applying an unrelated default.</strong> When no valid rate exists, block purchase or display a clear delivery-unavailable outcome.</div>","Free Shipping":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Questions</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Marketplace-wide</td><td>Who funds the seller entitlement and which products or regions are excluded?</td></tr><tr><td>Seller-specific</td><td>Does the threshold apply per seller and who maintains it?</td></tr><tr><td>Product-specific</td><td>Which variants use free shipping and how is profile assignment controlled?</td></tr><tr><td>Campaign</td><td>What are the dates, funding, commission, tax and refund rules?</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Whole-cart or per-seller threshold</li><li>Bulky, remote, express and international exclusions</li><li>Partial cancellation and return treatment</li><li>Customer wording</li><li>Cost and conversion reporting</li></ul>","Big and Bulky Products":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Objective weight, dimension or handling definition</li><li>Dedicated profile, zone, rate and carrier</li><li>Accurate packaged dimensions</li><li>Delivery type: kerbside, inside, room-of-choice or installation</li><li>Access and appointment information</li><li>Post-order additional-charge limits where unavoidable</li><li>Collection and return funding</li><li>Failed delivery and product-does-not-fit process</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Calculate accurately before payment wherever possible.</strong> Unexpected post-order freight charges should remain an approved exception, not the standard model.</div>","International Shipping":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Launch countries and approved sellers</li><li>Eligible and restricted products</li><li>Carrier and end-to-end tracking</li><li>Customs description, origin and harmonised codes</li><li>Duties, tax and customer wording</li><li>Currency and exchange-rate responsibility</li><li>Delivery promise and customs delay</li><li>International return or returnless policy</li><li>Successful destination test order</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Seller capability alone is not enough.</strong> Confirm customer service, customs, returns, payments and product restrictions before enabling a country.</div>","Carriers":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Approved carrier register and consistent names</li><li>Tracking URL or integration code</li><li>Countries, services and product limits</li><li>Seller permission and new-carrier request</li><li>Multiple fulfilment locations</li><li>Local delivery, click and collect or no-tracking evidence</li><li>Performance monitoring and deactivation process</li></ul><p>Avoid duplicate names such as different spellings of the same carrier because they fragment tracking and reporting.</p>","Tracking Requirements":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Carrier and tracking number at dispatch</li><li>Customer-accessible link</li><li>Products and quantities in each shipment</li><li>Exemptions for digital, pickup or approved local delivery</li><li>Validation beyond a non-empty field</li><li>Correction process and customer update</li><li>Missing-tracking monitoring and seller consequence</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>A tracking number is not necessarily valid tracking.</strong> Define the validation level your marketplace can support.</div>","Dispatch SLAs":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Clock start: order, invoice, notification or release</li><li>Business or calendar days</li><li>Cut-off, weekends and public holidays</li><li>Seller and product-specific exceptions</li><li>Partial fulfilment measurement</li><li>Customer delay communication</li><li>Watch, warning and critical thresholds</li><li>Evidence-based exclusions and consequences</li></ul><p>Separate dispatch from delivery. The seller controls preparation; the carrier controls much of the transit time.</p>","Partial Fulfilment":"<p>Allow several shipments or partial quantities only when the storefront, integration, seller and customer service processes can represent them accurately.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Line items and quantities per shipment</li><li>Carrier, tracking, date and fulfil-from address</li><li>Items still pending or cancelled</li><li>No unexpected additional customer charge</li><li>SLA treatment</li><li>Seller-invoice completion after every quantity resolves</li><li>Customer communication for each shipment</li><li>Integration and manual correction tests</li></ul>"},"related":[["shipping-strategy","Shipping Strategy"],["shipping-rules","Shipping Rules"],["fulfilment","Fulfilment"]]},"order-refund-decisions":{"summary":"Define order release, seller and customer cancellation, return channels, seller permissions, labels, return requirements, shipping responsibility, financial treatment and manual or API refund processing.","audience":["Customer service","Marketplace operations","Finance","Technology"],"sections":{"Order Hold vs Immediate Release":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Immediate release</th><th>Order hold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Sellers receive orders quickly and can begin fulfilment</td><td>Provides time for cancellation, fraud, payment or validation checks</td></tr><tr><td>Simpler integration with less intermediate state</td><td>Requires inventory reservation, release monitoring and failure recovery</td></tr><tr><td>Customer cancellation window is limited</td><td>Seller notification and dispatch SLA begin later</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>System controlling the hold</li><li>Duration and release trigger</li><li>Payment authorisation or capture</li><li>Inventory reservation and restoration</li><li>Customer status</li><li>Failed or duplicate release recovery</li><li>Exact dispatch-SLA start event</li></ul>","Seller Cancellation Permissions":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Sellers allowed to cancel before dispatch</li><li>Approved reasons and seller-fault classification</li><li>Full, line-item and quantity cancellation</li><li>Operator finalisation and payment refund</li><li>Customer communication owner</li><li>Inventory correction</li><li>Cancellation-rate monitoring and consequence</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Cancellation does not fix inventory.</strong> Require source stock correction so the same unavailable product does not receive another order.</div>","Customer Cancellation Process":"<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Request</strong><p>Customer uses the approved self-service or assisted channel.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Eligibility</strong><p>Check hold, dispatch and seller fulfilment state.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Decision</strong><p>Cancel eligible line items or explain why the request cannot be completed.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Finance</strong><p>Void or refund the correct product, shipping, tax and promotion amounts.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Communication</strong><p>Confirm the cancellation, remaining items and refund timing.</p></div></div></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Multi-seller and partial cancellation</li><li>Address-change alternative</li><li>Seller contact timing</li><li>Promotion and free-shipping recalculation</li><li>Declined request and post-dispatch return route</li></ul>","Return Request Channel":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Channel</th><th>Considerations</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Operator customer service</td><td>Strong policy control and suitable for lower launch volume</td></tr><tr><td>Self-service portal</td><td>Requires eligibility, Marketplacer, label, payment and status integration</td></tr><tr><td>Seller-direct</td><td>Needs approved customer-data access, seller SLA and operator visibility</td></tr><tr><td>In-store or specialist route</td><td>Requires clear handoff and marketplace record creation</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Information and evidence collected</li><li>Reason mapping</li><li>System creating the Marketplacer request</li><li>Customer-visible statuses</li><li>Duplicate-request prevention</li><li>Communication owner</li></ul>","Seller Refund Permissions":"<p>Separate the ability to start a post-dispatch request from the ability to decide the return path, assess the item and finalise the financial outcome.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Seller eligibility and training</li><li>Customer relationship model</li><li>Initiation permission</li><li>Return Required or returnless authority</li><li>Seller assessment and denial</li><li>Operator visibility and override</li><li>Permission suspension or removal</li><li>Duplicate notification control</li></ul>","Return Labels":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>What to define</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller-provided</td><td>Carrier account, funding, address and customer delivery</td></tr><tr><td>Operator-provided</td><td>Central carrier, cost allocation and return centre</td></tr><tr><td>Customer-arranged</td><td>Tracking, proof and customer cost policy</td></tr><tr><td>Collection or no label</td><td>Bulky, pickup, digital or returnless process</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Address label is not automatically prepaid.</strong> Use customer wording that reflects whether the carrier cost has actually been funded.</div>","Return Required vs Returnless":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Return Required for inspection, resale, repair, high value or fraud control</li><li>Returnless for low value, unsafe, perishable or uneconomic returns</li><li>Value and reason thresholds</li><li>Evidence and fraud controls</li><li>Seller, customer service and operator authority</li><li>Return deadline and assessment SLA</li><li>Denial, dispute and operator override</li></ul><p>Report returnless use and compare the product value, return freight and customer outcome.</p>","Return Shipping Responsibility":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Reason</th><th>Typical decision to document</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Change of mind</td><td>Customer or policy-defined funding</td></tr><tr><td>Faulty, damaged or incorrect product</td><td>Seller, carrier or operator funding</td></tr><tr><td>Operator goodwill</td><td>Operator funding unless later recovered</td></tr><tr><td>Product recall</td><td>Approved safety and recovery process</td></tr><tr><td>Bulky or international return</td><td>Collection, customs and specialist-cost authority</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Original outbound shipping</li><li>Return carrier or collection</li><li>Seller remittance deduction</li><li>Carrier claim</li><li>Multi-seller parcel separation</li><li>Seller agreement alignment</li></ul>","Commission and Fee Treatment":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Decision</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Item and tax</td><td>Customer refund and seller/operator funding</td></tr><tr><td>Postage</td><td>Customer refund and seller entitlement</td></tr><tr><td>Commission and postage commission</td><td>Reverse, retain or adjust</td></tr><tr><td>Merchant fee</td><td>Fixed and percentage treatment</td></tr><tr><td>Wholesale</td><td>Seller liability and operator margin</td></tr><tr><td>Promotion</td><td>Seller and operator contribution</td></tr><tr><td>After seller payout</td><td>Offset, negative balance, reserve or repayment</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Approve a reason-based financial matrix.</strong> Define the refund treatment for each financial component.</div>","Manual vs API Refund Processing":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Manual or hybrid launch</th><th>API automation</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Suitable for lower volume, policy learning and complex judgement</td><td>Suitable for self-service, scale and synchronised customer status</td></tr><tr><td>Requires queue ownership and reconciliation</td><td>Requires idempotency, status mapping, retries and monitoring</td></tr><tr><td>Portal workflow remains the fallback</td><td>Automation still needs manual exception tools</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Request source and identifiers</li><li>Cancellation versus return classification</li><li>Seller action</li><li>Payment refund trigger</li><li>Marketplacer finalisation</li><li>Customer statuses</li><li>Duplicate prevention</li><li>Failure monitoring and manual recovery</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Define what “Refunded” means in every system.</strong> Request approved, payment submitted and funds received are separate events.</div>"},"related":[["refund-foundations","Refund Foundations"],["return-workflow","Return Workflow"],["refund-integrations","Refund Integrations"]]},"integration-data-decisions":{"summary":"Define authoritative product, inventory and pricing sources, order and fulfilment routing, refund integration, MConnect settings, API and webhook ownership, monitoring and manual fallback.","audience":["Technology and integrations","Marketplace operations","Catalogue","Finance"],"sections":{"Product Source of Truth":"<p>Assign an authoritative system by field and document the update direction, frequency and override behaviour.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Possible authoritative source</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller IDs, SKU and barcode</td><td>Seller ecommerce, ERP or PIM</td></tr><tr><td>Source title, description and images</td><td>Seller PIM or ecommerce</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplace category, Brand and publication</td><td>Marketplacer</td></tr><tr><td>Shared Golden content</td><td>Central Product Database</td></tr><tr><td>Customer merchandising</td><td>Front-end or ecommerce layer</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Creation and update authority</li><li>Manual Marketplacer edit overwrite behaviour</li><li>Deletion and discontinuation</li><li>Stable cross-system identifiers</li><li>Conflict priority and audit</li></ul>","Inventory Source of Truth":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Physical, sellable, allocated or available-to-promise definition</li><li>Reservation event</li><li>Update frequency and maximum delay</li><li>Inventory buffer</li><li>Zero-stock and back-order treatment</li><li>Multi-location aggregation</li><li>Cancellation and stock restoration</li><li>Payment-success/order-failure recovery</li><li>Cross-system reconciliation</li></ul><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Describe stock as real time only when the complete flow supports real-time updates.</strong> State the expected delay and design a buffer where overselling risk requires it.</div>","Pricing Source of Truth":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Base, sale, wholesale, RRP, member and promotion price owner</li><li>Commission versus wholesale authority</li><li>Tax and currency</li><li>Operator override and approval</li><li>Price validation and margin floor</li><li>Checkout revalidation</li><li>Source sync and manual edit behaviour</li><li>Order and payment reconciliation</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Separate customer and supplier prices under wholesale.</strong> The website retail price is the customer-facing value controlled or approved by the Operator. Wholesale Price is the Seller entitlement basis. Seller RRP is reference only, and a wholesale promotional price changes supplier cost during approved dates without automatically changing the customer price.</div>","Order Routing":"<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Storefront</strong><p>Customer completes checkout and payment.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Integration</strong><p>Line items are mapped using stable marketplace identifiers.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Marketplacer</strong><p>The marketplace order and seller invoices are created.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Seller channel</strong><p>Each seller receives the order through its approved method.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Reconciliation</strong><p>Payment, customer order and seller records remain traceable.</p></div></div></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Order creation timing and hold</li><li>Line-item versus invoice input</li><li>First-party and marketplace item separation</li><li>Seller notification</li><li>External order and payment IDs</li><li>Idempotency and safe retry</li><li>Partial failure and paid-order recovery</li></ul>","Fulfilment Updates":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>System creating the shipment</li><li>Line item and quantity mapping</li><li>Partial fulfilment and several carriers</li><li>Carrier and tracking mapping</li><li>Shipment corrections</li><li>Customer notification owner</li><li>Invoice completion</li><li>Failed event and duplicate handling</li><li>Reconciliation across seller, Marketplacer and storefront</li></ul>","Refund Integration":"<p>Connect customer request, Marketplacer workflow, seller action, financial adjustment and payment refund without treating them as one event.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>System creating the request</li><li>Order, invoice, line-item, request and payment IDs</li><li>Cancellation, return and returnless mapping</li><li>Seller approval or assessment</li><li>Approved amount and components</li><li>Payment-provider refund trigger</li><li>Customer-visible status</li><li>Idempotency, retry and duplicate protection</li><li>Remittance adjustment and reconciliation</li></ul>","MConnect Settings":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Seller platform, store URL and authorised credentials</li><li>Product-selection tags, collections or exclusions</li><li>Automatic or manual sync</li><li>Fields that continue to update</li><li>Remove external description links</li><li>Only import new products with stock</li><li>Order, fulfilment and refund direction</li><li>Duplicate email notifications</li><li>Mapping and product governance after import</li><li>Connection failure and disconnection process</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>MConnect moves data; it does not define your catalogue.</strong> Imported products still need approved categories, attributes, shipping profiles and governance.</div>","API Responsibilities":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Owner to assign</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Business process and source-of-truth rules</td><td>Your business workstream</td></tr><tr><td>Architecture, code, idempotency and logging</td><td>Integration team</td></tr><tr><td>Credentials, security and rotation</td><td>Technology and security</td></tr><tr><td>Seller source system and data</td><td>Seller or partner</td></tr><tr><td>Monitoring, incident and fallback</td><td>Named support owners</td></tr><tr><td>Platform capability investigation</td><td>Marketplacer Support when applicable</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Sandbox and Production separation</li><li>API contract and status mapping</li><li>Stable identifiers</li><li>Validation and error categories</li><li>Safe retries after timeout</li><li>Deployment, rollback and documentation</li></ul>","Webhook Ownership":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Publisher, consumer, business owner and technical owner</li><li>Endpoint, authentication and environment</li><li>Event and payload identifiers</li><li>Fast acknowledgement and queued processing</li><li>Idempotency for duplicate delivery</li><li>Out-of-order event handling</li><li>Retry and permanent-failure process</li><li>Alert recipient, replay and manual recovery</li><li>Webhook register and support evidence</li></ul>","Error Monitoring":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Technical</td><td>Availability, authentication, queues, responses and retries</td></tr><tr><td>Data</td><td>Missing, duplicate, stale or inconsistent records</td></tr><tr><td>Business</td><td>Paid orders, seller receipt, shipment, refund and customer outcome</td></tr><tr><td>Reconciliation</td><td>Comparison between systems to detect silent failure</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Severity and response targets</li><li>First responder and business owner</li><li>Actionable alerts with identifiers</li><li>Customer and financial impact</li><li>Incident communication</li><li>Root cause and preventive action</li></ul>","Manual Fallback Processes":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Process</th><th>Possible fallback</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Products</td><td>Seller Portal or Bulk Product Management workbook; pause new imports</td></tr><tr><td>Inventory</td><td>Set stock to zero, bulk update or unpublish</td></tr><tr><td>Price</td><td>Keep last verified price, remove promotion or bulk update</td></tr><tr><td>Orders</td><td>Queue, pause checkout or authorised manual creation with duplicate checks</td></tr><tr><td>Fulfilment</td><td>Seller Portal or bulk dispatch</td></tr><tr><td>Refunds</td><td>Portal workflow and manual payment refund</td></tr><tr><td>Webhooks</td><td>Retrieve current state, replay safely or update downstream manually</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Activation threshold and authority</li><li>Maximum duration</li><li>Automation pause and duplicate prevention</li><li>Staff access and templates</li><li>Seller and customer communication</li><li>Reconciliation before resuming</li><li>Tested return to automation</li></ul>"},"related":[["mconnect","MConnect"],["apis","APIs"],["integration-troubleshooting","Integration Troubleshooting"]]},"marketplace-operations-decisions":{"summary":"Define customer and seller support ownership, incident escalation, seller SLA thresholds and reviews, finance reconciliation, product audits and reporting responsibilities for live marketplace operations.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Customer service","Seller management","Finance"],"sections":{"Customer Service Ownership":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>How it operates</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Operator-led</td><td>Your team receives, investigates and communicates all customer outcomes</td></tr><tr><td>Dedicated marketplace support</td><td>A specialist team handles marketplace orders while other support remains separate</td></tr><tr><td>Shared</td><td>Your team owns the customer and obtains evidence or decisions from sellers</td></tr><tr><td>Seller-direct</td><td>Approved enquiry types go to sellers under strict SLA and visibility rules</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>First-line, investigating and final-decision owner</li><li>Customer communication owner</li><li>Access to order, seller invoice, shipment, return and payment records</li><li>Financial authority limits</li><li>Seller response SLA and escalation</li><li>Service hours and urgent coverage</li><li>Case quality assurance</li></ul>","Seller Enquiry Process":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>One primary support channel</li><li>Categories for account, catalogue, order, refund, finance, integration and commercial questions</li><li>Required seller, environment and record identifiers</li><li>Acknowledgement and resolution targets</li><li>Urgent production path</li><li>Case ownership and history</li><li>Repeat-enquiry analysis and seller guidance improvement</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Keep operational questions in a shared case system.</strong> Private messages and individual inboxes make ownership, history and trends difficult to manage.</div>","Incident Escalation":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Severity</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Critical</td><td>Customers charged without orders, duplicate refunds, widespread outage, security or safety issue</td></tr><tr><td>High</td><td>Major seller cannot receive orders, stock or refunds failing at scale</td></tr><tr><td>Medium</td><td>Selected records or one seller affected with a workaround</td></tr><tr><td>Low</td><td>Cosmetic, informational or non-urgent reporting issue</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Incident lead and technical/business owners</li><li>Containment authority</li><li>Affected records and financial impact</li><li>Internal, seller and customer communications</li><li>Marketplacer or provider escalation evidence</li><li>Recovery and reconciliation</li><li>Post-incident root cause and prevention</li></ul>","Seller SLA Thresholds":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Dispatch time and breach rate</li><li>Seller-fault cancellation</li><li>Return and refund response</li><li>Tracking presence and validity</li><li>Catalogue correction and compliance response</li><li>Integration incident response</li><li>Target, watch, warning and critical levels</li><li>Minimum order sample and approved exclusions</li><li>Consequences by severity</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Use both percentages and volume.</strong> One failure in two orders is not the same evidence as fifty failures in one hundred orders.</div>","Performance Reviews":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Cadence</th><th>Focus</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Daily</td><td>Orders, tracking, returns, incidents and urgent product risk</td></tr><tr><td>Weekly</td><td>Seller health, SLA trends, catalogue and integration actions</td></tr><tr><td>Monthly</td><td>Scorecard, sales, customer outcomes, finance and corrective actions</td></tr><tr><td>Quarterly</td><td>Strategic growth, assortment, commercial terms and long-term performance</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Root-cause review</li><li>Corrective action owner, target and due date</li><li>Seller evidence and dispute path</li><li>Positive recognition and growth opportunities</li><li>Formal consequence for repeated or severe breach</li><li>Stored scorecards and meeting records</li></ul>","Finance Reconciliation":"<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Payment</strong><p>Confirm authorised and captured customer amount.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Order</strong><p>Match Marketplacer order, seller invoices, tax, shipping and promotions.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Commercial calculation</strong><p>Validate commission, wholesale, fees and seller liability.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Refund</strong><p>Match workflow, payment refund and remittance adjustment.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Remittance and payout</strong><p>Match eligibility, approval, provider instruction and settlement.</p></div></div></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Near-real-time payment/order controls</li><li>Daily order and refund exceptions</li><li>Weekly remittance and negative balance review</li><li>Monthly period close and tax</li><li>Stable reconciliation keys</li><li>Variance thresholds and payout holds</li><li>Separation of configuration, approval and reconciliation</li></ul>","Product Quality Audits":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Launch, new-seller, scheduled sample, triggered and full-catalogue audits</li><li>Identity, content, commercial, shipping and compliance dimensions</li><li>Risk-based sample including top sellers and high-return products</li><li>Critical, major and minor severity</li><li>Immediate takedown authority</li><li>Seller source correction and SLA</li><li>Use of Catalog Rules, mapping or transformations to prevent recurrence</li><li>Audit metrics and seller consequence</li></ul>","Reporting Responsibilities":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Report area</th><th>Typical owner</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Sales and commercial</td><td>Marketplace trading or commercial</td></tr><tr><td>Seller performance</td><td>Seller management or operations</td></tr><tr><td>Catalogue quality</td><td>Catalogue operations</td></tr><tr><td>Orders and fulfilment</td><td>Marketplace operations</td></tr><tr><td>Returns and refunds</td><td>Customer service, returns and finance</td></tr><tr><td>Finance and remittance</td><td>Finance</td></tr><tr><td>Integration health</td><td>Technology</td></tr><tr><td>Customer service</td><td>Customer service leadership</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Business question and metric definition</li><li>Authoritative source and filters</li><li>Owner, reviewer and recipients</li><li>Daily, weekly, monthly or quarterly cadence</li><li>Threshold that requires action</li><li>Privacy, access and retention</li><li>Validation and change control</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>A report is useful only when it changes action.</strong> Name who reviews it, what threshold matters and where the resulting action is tracked.</div>"},"related":[["daily-operations","Daily Marketplace Operations"],["seller-performance-reporting","Seller Performance Reporting"],["finance-reporting","Finance Reporting"]]},"marketplace-decision-register":{"summary":"Create one controlled record of the decisions that shape your marketplace, including ownership, deadlines, working positions, approvals, implementation and related training.","audience":["Marketplace lead","Project manager","Decision owners","Approvers"],"sections":{"Decision Owner":"<p>Assign one accountable owner to progress every decision. Contributors, approvers, implementers and reviewers can be separate.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>Responsibility</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Accountable owner</td><td>Defines the question, gathers input and ensures the decision is reached</td></tr><tr><td>Approver</td><td>Provides formal authority</td></tr><tr><td>Contributor</td><td>Provides specialist customer, commercial, legal, finance or technical input</td></tr><tr><td>Implementer</td><td>Configures the platform, process, integration or document</td></tr><tr><td>Reviewer</td><td>Validates the result</td></tr><tr><td>Informed party</td><td>Needs the outcome to perform related work</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Name one accountable owner.</strong> Use a person or role rather than a department name alone so responsibility for progressing the decision is clear.</div>","Required-By Date":"<p>Set the date according to the earliest activity that cannot proceed safely without the answer, not the final launch date.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision</th><th>Required before</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Tax model</td><td>Environment creation and integration design</td></tr><tr><td>Commission or wholesale</td><td>Seller agreement and financial configuration</td></tr><tr><td>Taxonomy and attributes</td><td>Seller product specification and mapping</td></tr><tr><td>Shipping model</td><td>Seller onboarding and checkout development</td></tr><tr><td>Returns and refund funding</td><td>Customer policy, seller agreement and finance process</td></tr><tr><td>Order routing</td><td>Integration build and end-to-end testing</td></tr></tbody></table></div><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Target date</li><li>Latest safe required-by date</li><li>Dependency</li><li>Escalation date</li><li>Effective date</li><li>Review or expiry date</li></ul><div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Record every change to an overdue date.</strong> Include the affected work, revised date and person accepting the risk.</div>","Working Position":"<p>Use a clearly labelled temporary position when discovery or approval is incomplete but selected work can continue.</p><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Proposed approach</li><li>Assumptions and evidence still required</li><li>Reason it is temporary</li><li>Known risks and accepted owner</li><li>Activities allowed to continue</li><li>Activities that must wait</li><li>Review and expiry date</li><li>Temporary approval</li></ul><div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>A working position is more than “TBC”.</strong> It must be specific enough to test and time-bound enough to prevent an assumption becoming permanent.</div>","Final Decision":"<p>Write the final position as a clear approved statement and connect it to implementation and verification.</p><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Decision question and final decision</td><td>Defines the approved marketplace position</td></tr><tr><td>Owner, approver and approval date</td><td>Records authority</td></tr><tr><td>Scope and effective date</td><td>Defines sellers, products, regions and timing</td></tr><tr><td>Rationale and alternatives</td><td>Preserves why the option was selected</td></tr><tr><td>Exceptions</td><td>Controls seller or scenario variation</td></tr><tr><td>Implementation tasks and owner</td><td>Converts policy into work</td></tr><tr><td>Evidence and verification</td><td>Proves configuration, testing and communication</td></tr><tr><td>Review date and status</td><td>Supports change control and future reassessment</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Approval is not implementation.</strong> Track configured, tested, communicated and verified as separate stages and preserve superseded decisions.</div>","Related Training Topic":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision area</th><th>Related topic</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Seller onboarding and performance</td><td>Seller, Product and Order Operations</td></tr><tr><td>Taxonomy, categories and Brands</td><td>Marketplace Structure</td></tr><tr><td>Commission, wholesale, tax and remittance</td><td>Marketplace Structure and Commercials</td></tr><tr><td>Shipping, orders and fulfilment</td><td>Seller, Product and Order Operations</td></tr><tr><td>Cancellations, returns and refunds</td><td>Refunds and Marketplace Finance</td></tr><tr><td>MConnect, APIs and webhooks</td><td>Integrations and Data Flow</td></tr><tr><td>Launch readiness</td><td>Testing and Go-Live</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Separate a platform question from a business decision and an implementation task. Training can explain what is possible; your organisation still approves what will apply.</p><h3>Sample Marketplace Decision Register</h3>\n<p>This illustrative register shows how a new Operator could record approved decisions, time-bound working positions and an at-risk dependency in one controlled view.</p>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Use this as an example, not a recommended marketplace configuration.</strong> Replace the owners, dates, statuses and positions with decisions approved for your marketplace. Commission and wholesale models may also coexist across different Sellers.</div>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead><tr><th>ID</th><th>Decision area</th><th>Decision question</th><th>Accountable owner</th><th>Required by</th><th>Status</th><th>Current position or approved outcome</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>DEC-001</td><td>Commercial model</td><td>Will Sellers operate on commission, wholesale or a mixed model?</td><td>Marketplace lead</td><td>Before Seller agreements and Finance configuration</td><td><span class=\"status later\">Approved</span></td><td>Use a mixed model. Commission is the default, with wholesale assigned only to approved Sellers and recorded at Seller level.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>DEC-002</td><td>Taxonomy</td><td>Which taxonomy will Sellers map their Products into?</td><td>Catalogue lead</td><td>Before Product specifications and ingestion</td><td><span class=\"status later\">Approved</span></td><td>Use the Marketplacer global taxonomy as the Seller-facing Product structure. The customer-facing storefront navigation may be curated separately.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>DEC-003</td><td>Product governance</td><td>Which Products and Product changes require vetting?</td><td>Catalogue lead</td><td>Before the first Product import</td><td><span class=\"status consider\">Working position</span></td><td>Vet all launch Seller Products and material Product changes. Review the approach after the first 90 days of business-as-usual operations.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>DEC-004</td><td>Shipping and fulfilment</td><td>Who owns shipping rates, tracking and fulfilment promises?</td><td>Marketplace Operations lead</td><td>Before Seller onboarding and checkout validation</td><td><span class=\"status later\">Approved</span></td><td>Sellers use approved shipping profiles and provide tracking for dispatched Orders. Operator approval is required for exceptions.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>DEC-005</td><td>Cancellations, returns and refunds</td><td>How are cancellation, return, customer cash refund and Seller adjustment separated?</td><td>Customer Service and Finance leads</td><td>Before customer policy publication and end-to-end testing</td><td><span class=\"status later\">Approved</span></td><td>Use cancellation before dispatch and the return workflow after dispatch. The payment provider executes the customer cash refund, while Marketplacer records Invoice Amendments and Seller remittance adjustments.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>DEC-006</td><td>Seller payout</td><td>Which payout method and approval cadence will apply?</td><td>Finance lead</td><td>Before live Seller transactions</td><td><span class=\"status required\">At risk</span></td><td>MPay suitability is still being assessed. Manual payout approval and reconciliation remain the working process until Finance completes sign-off.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>DEC-007</td><td>Integration and data ownership</td><td>Which systems own Product, stock, payment and marketplace financial records?</td><td>Technology lead</td><td>Before integration build</td><td><span class=\"status later\">Approved</span></td><td>The Seller source owns Product and stock data, the storefront and payment provider own checkout and payment references, and Marketplacer owns the marketplace Order, refund and remittance record.</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Keep the register operational.</strong> A decision is not complete until the approved position has been implemented, tested, communicated and linked to evidence.</div><h3>Recommended register fields</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Decision ID and area</li><li>Decision question</li><li>Accountable owner and approver</li><li>Priority and required-by date</li><li>Dependency</li><li>Working position, assumptions and risk</li><li>Final decision, rationale and scope</li><li>Exceptions and effective date</li><li>Related training and configuration</li><li>Implementation owner, status and evidence</li><li>Review date and notes</li></ul><h3>Review cadence</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Review new, due, at-risk and blocked decisions weekly.</li><li>Update the register after each training and discovery session.</li><li>Check seller-specific decisions before each onboarding begins.</li><li>Close or formally accept every launch-critical decision before go-live.</li><li>Review working positions against real post-launch volume and performance.</li></ul>"},"related":[["how-decisions-work","How Marketplace Decisions Work"],["decision-timeline","Decision Timeline"],["onboarding-to-launch","From Onboarding to Launch"]]}};
